60// Version
61// (Integer encoded as XYYZZ for use in #if preprocessor conditionals. Work in progress versions typically starts at XYY99 then bounce up to XYY00, XYY01 etc. when release tagging happens)
62#define IMGUI_VERSION "1.75"
63#define IMGUI_VERSION_NUM 17500
64#define IMGUI_CHECKVERSION() ImGui::DebugCheckVersionAndDataLayout(IMGUI_VERSION, sizeof(ImGuiIO), sizeof(ImGuiStyle), sizeof(ImVec2), sizeof(ImVec4), sizeof(ImDrawVert), sizeof(ImDrawIdx))

66// Define attributes of all API symbols declarations (e.g. for DLL under Windows)
67// IMGUI_API is used for core imgui functions, IMGUI_IMPL_API is used for the default bindings files (imgui_impl_xxx.h)
68// Using dear imgui via a shared library is not recommended, because of function call overhead and because we don't guarantee backward nor forward ABI compatibility.
69#ifndef IMGUI_API
70#define IMGUI_API
71#endif
72#ifndef IMGUI_IMPL_API
73#define IMGUI_IMPL_API IMGUI_API
74#endif

76// Helper Macros
77#ifndef IM_ASSERT
78#include <assert.h>
79#define IM_ASSERT(_EXPR) assert(_EXPR) // You can override the default assert handler by editing imconfig.h
80#endif
81#if !defined(IMGUI_USE_STB_SPRINTF) && (defined(__clang__) || defined(__GNUC__))
82#define IM_FMTARGS(FMT) __attribute__((format(printf, FMT, FMT+1))) // To apply printf-style warnings to our functions.
83#define IM_FMTLIST(FMT) __attribute__((format(printf, FMT, 0)))
84#else
85#define IM_FMTARGS(FMT)
86#define IM_FMTLIST(FMT)
87#endif
88#define IM_ARRAYSIZE(_ARR) ((int)(sizeof(_ARR) / sizeof(*_ARR))) // Size of a static C-style array. Don't use on pointers!
89#define IM_UNUSED(_VAR) ((void)_VAR) // Used to silence "unused variable warnings". Often useful as asserts may be stripped out from final builds.
90#if (__cplusplus >= 201100)
91#define IM_OFFSETOF(_TYPE,_MEMBER) offsetof(_TYPE, _MEMBER) // Offset of _MEMBER within _TYPE. Standardized as offsetof() in C++11
92#else
93#define IM_OFFSETOF(_TYPE,_MEMBER) ((size_t)&(((_TYPE*)0)->_MEMBER)) // Offset of _MEMBER within _TYPE. Old style macro.
94#endif
95#define IM_UNICODE_CODEPOINT_MAX 0xFFFF // Last Unicode code point supported by this build.
96#define IM_UNICODE_CODEPOINT_INVALID 0xFFFD // Standard invalid Unicode code point.

98// Warnings
99#if defined(__clang__)
100#pragma clang diagnostic push
101#pragma clang diagnostic ignored "-Wold-style-cast"
102#if __has_warning("-Wzero-as-null-pointer-constant")
103#pragma clang diagnostic ignored "-Wzero-as-null-pointer-constant"
104#endif
105#elif defined(__GNUC__)
106#pragma GCC diagnostic push
107#pragma GCC diagnostic ignored "-Wpragmas" // warning: unknown option after '#pragma GCC diagnostic' kind
108#pragma GCC diagnostic ignored "-Wclass-memaccess" // [__GNUC__ >= 8] warning: 'memset/memcpy' clearing/writing an object of type 'xxxx' with no trivial copy-assignment; use assignment or value-initialization instead
109#endif

111//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
112// Forward declarations and basic types
113//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
114
115struct ImDrawChannel; // Temporary storage to output draw commands out of order, used by ImDrawListSplitter and ImDrawList::ChannelsSplit()
116struct ImDrawCmd; // A single draw command within a parent ImDrawList (generally maps to 1 GPU draw call, unless it is a callback)
117struct ImDrawData; // All draw command lists required to render the frame + pos/size coordinates to use for the projection matrix.
118struct ImDrawList; // A single draw command list (generally one per window, conceptually you may see this as a dynamic "mesh" builder)
119struct ImDrawListSharedData; // Data shared among multiple draw lists (typically owned by parent ImGui context, but you may create one yourself)
120struct ImDrawListSplitter; // Helper to split a draw list into different layers which can be drawn into out of order, then flattened back.
121struct ImDrawVert; // A single vertex (pos + uv + col = 20 bytes by default. Override layout with IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT)
122struct ImFont; // Runtime data for a single font within a parent ImFontAtlas
123struct ImFontAtlas; // Runtime data for multiple fonts, bake multiple fonts into a single texture, TTF/OTF font loader
124struct ImFontConfig; // Configuration data when adding a font or merging fonts
125struct ImFontGlyph; // A single font glyph (code point + coordinates within in ImFontAtlas + offset)
126struct ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder; // Helper to build glyph ranges from text/string data
127struct ImColor; // Helper functions to create a color that can be converted to either u32 or float4 (*OBSOLETE* please avoid using)
128struct ImGuiContext; // Dear ImGui context (opaque structure, unless including imgui_internal.h)
129struct ImGuiIO; // Main configuration and I/O between your application and ImGui
130struct ImGuiInputTextCallbackData; // Shared state of InputText() when using custom ImGuiInputTextCallback (rare/advanced use)
131struct ImGuiListClipper; // Helper to manually clip large list of items
132struct ImGuiOnceUponAFrame; // Helper for running a block of code not more than once a frame, used by IMGUI_ONCE_UPON_A_FRAME macro
133struct ImGuiPayload; // User data payload for drag and drop operations
134struct ImGuiSizeCallbackData; // Callback data when using SetNextWindowSizeConstraints() (rare/advanced use)
135struct ImGuiStorage; // Helper for key->value storage
136struct ImGuiStyle; // Runtime data for styling/colors
137struct ImGuiTextBuffer; // Helper to hold and append into a text buffer (~string builder)
138struct ImGuiTextFilter; // Helper to parse and apply text filters (e.g. "aaaaa[,bbbb][,ccccc]")
139
140// Typedefs and Enums/Flags (declared as int for compatibility with old C++, to allow using as flags and to not pollute the top of this file)
141// Use your programming IDE "Go to definition" facility on the names in the central column below to find the actual flags/enum lists.
142#ifndef ImTextureID
143typedef void* ImTextureID; // User data to identify a texture (this is whatever to you want it to be! read the FAQ about ImTextureID in imgui.cpp)
144#endif
145typedef unsigned int ImGuiID; // Unique ID used by widgets (typically hashed from a stack of string)
146typedef unsigned short ImWchar; // A single U16 character for keyboard input/display. We encode them as multi bytes UTF-8 when used in strings.
147typedef int ImGuiCol; // -> enum ImGuiCol_ // Enum: A color identifier for styling
148typedef int ImGuiCond; // -> enum ImGuiCond_ // Enum: A condition for many Set*() functions
149typedef int ImGuiDataType; // -> enum ImGuiDataType_ // Enum: A primary data type
150typedef int ImGuiDir; // -> enum ImGuiDir_ // Enum: A cardinal direction
151typedef int ImGuiKey; // -> enum ImGuiKey_ // Enum: A key identifier (ImGui-side enum)
152typedef int ImGuiNavInput; // -> enum ImGuiNavInput_ // Enum: An input identifier for navigation
153typedef int ImGuiMouseButton; // -> enum ImGuiMouseButton_ // Enum: A mouse button identifier (0=left, 1=right, 2=middle)
154typedef int ImGuiMouseCursor; // -> enum ImGuiMouseCursor_ // Enum: A mouse cursor identifier
155typedef int ImGuiStyleVar; // -> enum ImGuiStyleVar_ // Enum: A variable identifier for styling
156typedef int ImDrawCornerFlags; // -> enum ImDrawCornerFlags_ // Flags: for ImDrawList::AddRect(), AddRectFilled() etc.
157typedef int ImDrawListFlags; // -> enum ImDrawListFlags_ // Flags: for ImDrawList
158typedef int ImFontAtlasFlags; // -> enum ImFontAtlasFlags_ // Flags: for ImFontAtlas
159typedef int ImGuiBackendFlags; // -> enum ImGuiBackendFlags_ // Flags: for io.BackendFlags
160typedef int ImGuiColorEditFlags; // -> enum ImGuiColorEditFlags_ // Flags: for ColorEdit4(), ColorPicker4() etc.
161typedef int ImGuiConfigFlags; // -> enum ImGuiConfigFlags_ // Flags: for io.ConfigFlags
162typedef int ImGuiComboFlags; // -> enum ImGuiComboFlags_ // Flags: for BeginCombo()
163typedef int ImGuiDragDropFlags; // -> enum ImGuiDragDropFlags_ // Flags: for BeginDragDropSource(), AcceptDragDropPayload()
164typedef int ImGuiFocusedFlags; // -> enum ImGuiFocusedFlags_ // Flags: for IsWindowFocused()
165typedef int ImGuiHoveredFlags; // -> enum ImGuiHoveredFlags_ // Flags: for IsItemHovered(), IsWindowHovered() etc.
166typedef int ImGuiInputTextFlags; // -> enum ImGuiInputTextFlags_ // Flags: for InputText(), InputTextMultiline()
167typedef int ImGuiSelectableFlags; // -> enum ImGuiSelectableFlags_ // Flags: for Selectable()
168typedef int ImGuiTabBarFlags; // -> enum ImGuiTabBarFlags_ // Flags: for BeginTabBar()
169typedef int ImGuiTabItemFlags; // -> enum ImGuiTabItemFlags_ // Flags: for BeginTabItem()
170typedef int ImGuiTreeNodeFlags; // -> enum ImGuiTreeNodeFlags_ // Flags: for TreeNode(), TreeNodeEx(), CollapsingHeader()
171typedef int ImGuiWindowFlags; // -> enum ImGuiWindowFlags_ // Flags: for Begin(), BeginChild()
172typedef int (*ImGuiInputTextCallback)(ImGuiInputTextCallbackData *data);
173typedef void (*ImGuiSizeCallback)(ImGuiSizeCallbackData* data);
174
175// Scalar data types
176typedef signed char ImS8; // 8-bit signed integer
177typedef unsigned char ImU8; // 8-bit unsigned integer
178typedef signed short ImS16; // 16-bit signed integer
179typedef unsigned short ImU16; // 16-bit unsigned integer
180typedef signed int ImS32; // 32-bit signed integer == int
181typedef unsigned int ImU32; // 32-bit unsigned integer (often used to store packed colors)
182#if defined(_MSC_VER) && !defined(__clang__)
183typedef signed __int64 ImS64; // 64-bit signed integer (pre and post C++11 with Visual Studio)
184typedef unsigned __int64 ImU64; // 64-bit unsigned integer (pre and post C++11 with Visual Studio)
185#elif (defined(__clang__) || defined(__GNUC__)) && (__cplusplus < 201100)
186#include <stdint.h>
187typedef int64_t ImS64; // 64-bit signed integer (pre C++11)
188typedef uint64_t ImU64; // 64-bit unsigned integer (pre C++11)
189#else
190typedef signed long long ImS64; // 64-bit signed integer (post C++11)
191typedef unsigned long long ImU64; // 64-bit unsigned integer (post C++11)
192#endif
193
194// 2D vector (often used to store positions, sizes, etc.)
195struct ImVec2
196{
197 float x, y;
198 ImVec2() { x = y = 0.0f; }
199 ImVec2(float _x, float _y) { x = _x; y = _y; }
200 float operator[] (size_t idx) const { IM_ASSERT(idx <= 1); return (&x)[idx]; } // We very rarely use this [] operator, the assert overhead is fine.
201 float& operator[] (size_t idx) { IM_ASSERT(idx <= 1); return (&x)[idx]; } // We very rarely use this [] operator, the assert overhead is fine.
202#ifdef IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA
203 IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA // Define additional constructors and implicit cast operators in imconfig.h to convert back and forth between your math types and ImVec2.
204#endif
205};
206
207// 4D vector (often used to store floating-point colors)
208struct ImVec4
209{
210 float x, y, z, w;
211 ImVec4() { x = y = z = w = 0.0f; }
212 ImVec4(float _x, float _y, float _z, float _w) { x = _x; y = _y; z = _z; w = _w; }
213#ifdef IM_VEC4_CLASS_EXTRA
214 IM_VEC4_CLASS_EXTRA // Define additional constructors and implicit cast operators in imconfig.h to convert back and forth between your math types and ImVec4.
215#endif
216};

223namespace ImGui

225 // Context creation and access
226 // Each context create its own ImFontAtlas by default. You may instance one yourself and pass it to CreateContext() to share a font atlas between imgui contexts.
227 // None of those functions is reliant on the current context.
228 IMGUI_API ImGuiContext* CreateContext(ImFontAtlas* shared_font_atlas = NULL);
229 IMGUI_API void DestroyContext(ImGuiContext* ctx = NULL); // NULL = destroy current context
230 IMGUI_API ImGuiContext* GetCurrentContext();
231 IMGUI_API void SetCurrentContext(ImGuiContext* ctx);
232 IMGUI_API bool DebugCheckVersionAndDataLayout(const char* version_str, size_t sz_io, size_t sz_style, size_t sz_vec2, size_t sz_vec4, size_t sz_drawvert, size_t sz_drawidx);
233
234 // Main
235 IMGUI_API ImGuiIO& GetIO(); // access the IO structure (mouse/keyboard/gamepad inputs, time, various configuration options/flags)
236 IMGUI_API ImGuiStyle& GetStyle(); // access the Style structure (colors, sizes). Always use PushStyleCol(), PushStyleVar() to modify style mid-frame.
237 IMGUI_API void NewFrame(); // start a new Dear ImGui frame, you can submit any command from this point until Render()/EndFrame().
238 IMGUI_API void EndFrame(); // ends the Dear ImGui frame. automatically called by Render(), you likely don't need to call that yourself directly. If you don't need to render data (skipping rendering) you may call EndFrame() but you'll have wasted CPU already! If you don't need to render, better to not create any imgui windows and not call NewFrame() at all!
239 IMGUI_API void Render(); // ends the Dear ImGui frame, finalize the draw data. You can get call GetDrawData() to obtain it and run your rendering function. (Obsolete: this used to call io.RenderDrawListsFn(). Nowadays, we allow and prefer calling your render function yourself.)
240 IMGUI_API ImDrawData* GetDrawData(); // valid after Render() and until the next call to NewFrame(). this is what you have to render.
241
242 // Demo, Debug, Information
243 IMGUI_API void ShowDemoWindow(bool* p_open = NULL); // create Demo window (previously called ShowTestWindow). demonstrate most ImGui features. call this to learn about the library! try to make it always available in your application!
244 IMGUI_API void ShowAboutWindow(bool* p_open = NULL); // create About window. display Dear ImGui version, credits and build/system information.
245 IMGUI_API void ShowMetricsWindow(bool* p_open = NULL); // create Metrics/Debug window. display Dear ImGui internals: draw commands (with individual draw calls and vertices), window list, basic internal state, etc.
246 IMGUI_API void ShowStyleEditor(ImGuiStyle* ref = NULL); // add style editor block (not a window). you can pass in a reference ImGuiStyle structure to compare to, revert to and save to (else it uses the default style)
247 IMGUI_API bool ShowStyleSelector(const char* label); // add style selector block (not a window), essentially a combo listing the default styles.
248 IMGUI_API void ShowFontSelector(const char* label); // add font selector block (not a window), essentially a combo listing the loaded fonts.
249 IMGUI_API void ShowUserGuide(); // add basic help/info block (not a window): how to manipulate ImGui as a end-user (mouse/keyboard controls).
250 IMGUI_API const char* GetVersion(); // get the compiled version string e.g. "1.23" (essentially the compiled value for IMGUI_VERSION)
251
252 // Styles
253 IMGUI_API void StyleColorsDark(ImGuiStyle* dst = NULL); // new, recommended style (default)
254 IMGUI_API void StyleColorsClassic(ImGuiStyle* dst = NULL); // classic imgui style
255 IMGUI_API void StyleColorsLight(ImGuiStyle* dst = NULL); // best used with borders and a custom, thicker font

257 // Windows
258 // - Begin() = push window to the stack and start appending to it. End() = pop window from the stack.
259 // - You may append multiple times to the same window during the same frame.
260 // - Passing 'bool* p_open != NULL' shows a window-closing widget in the upper-right corner of the window,
261 // which clicking will set the boolean to false when clicked.
262 // - Begin() return false to indicate the window is collapsed or fully clipped, so you may early out and omit submitting
263 // anything to the window. Always call a matching End() for each Begin() call, regardless of its return value!
264 // [Important: due to legacy reason, this is inconsistent with most other functions such as BeginMenu/EndMenu,
265 // BeginPopup/EndPopup, etc. where the EndXXX call should only be called if the corresponding BeginXXX function
266 // returned true. Begin and BeginChild are the only odd ones out. Will be fixed in a future update.]
267 // - Note that the bottom of window stack always contains a window called "Debug".
268 IMGUI_API bool Begin(const char* name, bool* p_open = NULL, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0);
269 IMGUI_API void End();
270
271 // Child Windows
272 // - Use child windows to begin into a self-contained independent scrolling/clipping regions within a host window. Child windows can embed their own child.
273 // - For each independent axis of 'size': ==0.0f: use remaining host window size / >0.0f: fixed size / <0.0f: use remaining window size minus abs(size) / Each axis can use a different mode, e.g. ImVec2(0,400).
274 // - BeginChild() returns false to indicate the window is collapsed or fully clipped, so you may early out and omit submitting anything to the window.
275 // Always call a matching EndChild() for each BeginChild() call, regardless of its return value [as with Begin: this is due to legacy reason and inconsistent with most BeginXXX functions apart from the regular Begin() which behaves like BeginChild().]
276 IMGUI_API bool BeginChild(const char* str_id, const ImVec2& size = ImVec2(0,0), bool border = false, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0);
277 IMGUI_API bool BeginChild(ImGuiID id, const ImVec2& size = ImVec2(0,0), bool border = false, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0);
278 IMGUI_API void EndChild();
279
280 // Windows Utilities
281 // - 'current window' = the window we are appending into while inside a Begin()/End() block. 'next window' = next window we will Begin() into.
282 IMGUI_API bool IsWindowAppearing();
283 IMGUI_API bool IsWindowCollapsed();
284 IMGUI_API bool IsWindowFocused(ImGuiFocusedFlags flags=0); // is current window focused? or its root/child, depending on flags. see flags for options.
285 IMGUI_API bool IsWindowHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags flags=0); // is current window hovered (and typically: not blocked by a popup/modal)? see flags for options. NB: If you are trying to check whether your mouse should be dispatched to imgui or to your app, you should use the 'io.WantCaptureMouse' boolean for that! Please read the FAQ!
286 IMGUI_API ImDrawList* GetWindowDrawList(); // get draw list associated to the current window, to append your own drawing primitives
287 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetWindowPos(); // get current window position in screen space (useful if you want to do your own drawing via the DrawList API)
288 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetWindowSize(); // get current window size
289 IMGUI_API float GetWindowWidth(); // get current window width (shortcut for GetWindowSize().x)
290 IMGUI_API float GetWindowHeight(); // get current window height (shortcut for GetWindowSize().y)
291
292 // Prefer using SetNextXXX functions (before Begin) rather that SetXXX functions (after Begin).
293 IMGUI_API void SetNextWindowPos(const ImVec2& pos, ImGuiCond cond = 0, const ImVec2& pivot = ImVec2(0,0)); // set next window position. call before Begin(). use pivot=(0.5f,0.5f) to center on given point, etc.
294 IMGUI_API void SetNextWindowSize(const ImVec2& size, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // set next window size. set axis to 0.0f to force an auto-fit on this axis. call before Begin()
295 IMGUI_API void SetNextWindowSizeConstraints(const ImVec2& size_min, const ImVec2& size_max, ImGuiSizeCallback custom_callback = NULL, void* custom_callback_data = NULL); // set next window size limits. use -1,-1 on either X/Y axis to preserve the current size. Sizes will be rounded down. Use callback to apply non-trivial programmatic constraints.
296 IMGUI_API void SetNextWindowContentSize(const ImVec2& size); // set next window content size (~ scrollable client area, which enforce the range of scrollbars). Not including window decorations (title bar, menu bar, etc.) nor WindowPadding. set an axis to 0.0f to leave it automatic. call before Begin()
297 IMGUI_API void SetNextWindowCollapsed(bool collapsed, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // set next window collapsed state. call before Begin()
298 IMGUI_API void SetNextWindowFocus(); // set next window to be focused / top-most. call before Begin()
299 IMGUI_API void SetNextWindowBgAlpha(float alpha); // set next window background color alpha. helper to easily override the Alpha component of ImGuiCol_WindowBg/ChildBg/PopupBg. you may also use ImGuiWindowFlags_NoBackground.
300 IMGUI_API void SetWindowPos(const ImVec2& pos, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // (not recommended) set current window position - call within Begin()/End(). prefer using SetNextWindowPos(), as this may incur tearing and side-effects.
301 IMGUI_API void SetWindowSize(const ImVec2& size, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // (not recommended) set current window size - call within Begin()/End(). set to ImVec2(0,0) to force an auto-fit. prefer using SetNextWindowSize(), as this may incur tearing and minor side-effects.
302 IMGUI_API void SetWindowCollapsed(bool collapsed, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // (not recommended) set current window collapsed state. prefer using SetNextWindowCollapsed().
303 IMGUI_API void SetWindowFocus(); // (not recommended) set current window to be focused / top-most. prefer using SetNextWindowFocus().
304 IMGUI_API void SetWindowFontScale(float scale); // set font scale. Adjust IO.FontGlobalScale if you want to scale all windows. This is an old API! For correct scaling, prefer to reload font + rebuild ImFontAtlas + call style.ScaleAllSizes().
305 IMGUI_API void SetWindowPos(const char* name, const ImVec2& pos, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // set named window position.
306 IMGUI_API void SetWindowSize(const char* name, const ImVec2& size, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // set named window size. set axis to 0.0f to force an auto-fit on this axis.
307 IMGUI_API void SetWindowCollapsed(const char* name, bool collapsed, ImGuiCond cond = 0); // set named window collapsed state
308 IMGUI_API void SetWindowFocus(const char* name); // set named window to be focused / top-most. use NULL to remove focus.

326 IMGUI_API void SetScrollHereY(float center_y_ratio = 0.5f); // adjust scrolling amount to make current cursor position visible. center_y_ratio=0.0: top, 0.5: center, 1.0: bottom. When using to make a "default/current item" visible, consider using SetItemDefaultFocus() instead.

328 IMGUI_API void SetScrollFromPosY(float local_y, float center_y_ratio = 0.5f); // adjust scrolling amount to make given position visible. Generally GetCursorStartPos() + offset to compute a valid position.

359 // Cursor / Layout
360 // - By "cursor" we mean the current output position.
361 // - The typical widget behavior is to output themselves at the current cursor position, then move the cursor one line down.
362 // - You can call SameLine() between widgets to undo the last carriage return and output at the right of the preceeding widget.
363 IMGUI_API void Separator(); // separator, generally horizontal. inside a menu bar or in horizontal layout mode, this becomes a vertical separator.
364 IMGUI_API void SameLine(float offset_from_start_x=0.0f, float spacing=-1.0f); // call between widgets or groups to layout them horizontally. X position given in window coordinates.
365 IMGUI_API void NewLine(); // undo a SameLine() or force a new line when in an horizontal-layout context.
366 IMGUI_API void Spacing(); // add vertical spacing.
367 IMGUI_API void Dummy(const ImVec2& size); // add a dummy item of given size. unlike InvisibleButton(), Dummy() won't take the mouse click or be navigable into.
368 IMGUI_API void Indent(float indent_w = 0.0f); // move content position toward the right, by style.IndentSpacing or indent_w if != 0
369 IMGUI_API void Unindent(float indent_w = 0.0f); // move content position back to the left, by style.IndentSpacing or indent_w if != 0
370 IMGUI_API void BeginGroup(); // lock horizontal starting position
371 IMGUI_API void EndGroup(); // unlock horizontal starting position + capture the whole group bounding box into one "item" (so you can use IsItemHovered() or layout primitives such as SameLine() on whole group, etc.)
372 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetCursorPos(); // cursor position in window coordinates (relative to window position)
373 IMGUI_API float GetCursorPosX(); // (some functions are using window-relative coordinates, such as: GetCursorPos, GetCursorStartPos, GetContentRegionMax, GetWindowContentRegion* etc.
374 IMGUI_API float GetCursorPosY(); // other functions such as GetCursorScreenPos or everything in ImDrawList::
375 IMGUI_API void SetCursorPos(const ImVec2& local_pos); // are using the main, absolute coordinate system.
376 IMGUI_API void SetCursorPosX(float local_x); // GetWindowPos() + GetCursorPos() == GetCursorScreenPos() etc.)
377 IMGUI_API void SetCursorPosY(float local_y); //
378 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetCursorStartPos(); // initial cursor position in window coordinates
379 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetCursorScreenPos(); // cursor position in absolute screen coordinates [0..io.DisplaySize] (useful to work with ImDrawList API)
380 IMGUI_API void SetCursorScreenPos(const ImVec2& pos); // cursor position in absolute screen coordinates [0..io.DisplaySize]
381 IMGUI_API void AlignTextToFramePadding(); // vertically align upcoming text baseline to FramePadding.y so that it will align properly to regularly framed items (call if you have text on a line before a framed item)
382 IMGUI_API float GetTextLineHeight(); // ~ FontSize

387 // ID stack/scopes
388 // - Read the FAQ for more details about how ID are handled in dear imgui. If you are creating widgets in a loop you most
389 // likely want to push a unique identifier (e.g. object pointer, loop index) to uniquely differentiate them.
390 // - The resulting ID are hashes of the entire stack.
391 // - You can also use the "Label##foobar" syntax within widget label to distinguish them from each others.
392 // - In this header file we use the "label"/"name" terminology to denote a string that will be displayed and used as an ID,
393 // whereas "str_id" denote a string that is only used as an ID and not normally displayed.
394 IMGUI_API void PushID(const char* str_id); // push string into the ID stack (will hash string).
395 IMGUI_API void PushID(const char* str_id_begin, const char* str_id_end); // push string into the ID stack (will hash string).
396 IMGUI_API void PushID(const void* ptr_id); // push pointer into the ID stack (will hash pointer).
397 IMGUI_API void PushID(int int_id); // push integer into the ID stack (will hash integer).
398 IMGUI_API void PopID(); // pop from the ID stack.
399 IMGUI_API ImGuiID GetID(const char* str_id); // calculate unique ID (hash of whole ID stack + given parameter). e.g. if you want to query into ImGuiStorage yourself
400 IMGUI_API ImGuiID GetID(const char* str_id_begin, const char* str_id_end);
401 IMGUI_API ImGuiID GetID(const void* ptr_id);

Roughly equivalent to Text("%s", text) but: A) doesn't require null terminated string if 'text_end' is specified, B) it's faster, no memory copy is done, no buffer size limits, recommended for long chunks of text.

443 // Widgets: Drags
444 // - CTRL+Click on any drag box to turn them into an input box. Manually input values aren't clamped and can go off-bounds.
445 // - For all the Float2/Float3/Float4/Int2/Int3/Int4 versions of every functions, note that a 'float v[X]' function argument is the same as 'float* v', the array syntax is just a way to document the number of elements that are expected to be accessible. You can pass address of your first element out of a contiguous set, e.g. &myvector.x
446 // - Adjust format string to decorate the value with a prefix, a suffix, or adapt the editing and display precision e.g. "%.3f" -> 1.234; "%5.2f secs" -> 01.23 secs; "Biscuit: %.0f" -> Biscuit: 1; etc.
447 // - Speed are per-pixel of mouse movement (v_speed=0.2f: mouse needs to move by 5 pixels to increase value by 1). For gamepad/keyboard navigation, minimum speed is Max(v_speed, minimum_step_at_given_precision).
448 // - Use v_min < v_max to clamp edits to given limits. Note that CTRL+Click manual input can override those limits.
449 // - Use v_max = FLT_MAX / INT_MAX etc to avoid clamping to a maximum, same with v_min = -FLT_MAX / INT_MIN to avoid clamping to a minimum.
450 // - Use v_min > v_max to lock edits.
451 IMGUI_API bool DragFloat(const char* label, float* v, float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", float power = 1.0f); // If v_min >= v_max we have no bound
452 IMGUI_API bool DragFloat2(const char* label, float v[2], float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", float power = 1.0f);
453 IMGUI_API bool DragFloat3(const char* label, float v[3], float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", float power = 1.0f);
454 IMGUI_API bool DragFloat4(const char* label, float v[4], float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", float power = 1.0f);
455 IMGUI_API bool DragFloatRange2(const char* label, float* v_current_min, float* v_current_max, float v_speed = 1.0f, float v_min = 0.0f, float v_max = 0.0f, const char* format = "%.3f", const char* format_max = NULL, float power = 1.0f);
456 IMGUI_API bool DragInt(const char* label, int* v, float v_speed = 1.0f, int v_min = 0, int v_max = 0, const char* format = "%d"); // If v_min >= v_max we have no bound
457 IMGUI_API bool DragInt2(const char* label, int v[2], float v_speed = 1.0f, int v_min = 0, int v_max = 0, const char* format = "%d");
458 IMGUI_API bool DragInt3(const char* label, int v[3], float v_speed = 1.0f, int v_min = 0, int v_max = 0, const char* format = "%d");
459 IMGUI_API bool DragInt4(const char* label, int v[4], float v_speed = 1.0f, int v_min = 0, int v_max = 0, const char* format = "%d");
460 IMGUI_API bool DragIntRange2(const char* label, int* v_current_min, int* v_current_max, float v_speed = 1.0f, int v_min = 0, int v_max = 0, const char* format = "%d", const char* format_max = NULL);
461 IMGUI_API bool DragScalar(const char* label, ImGuiDataType data_type, void* p_data, float v_speed, const void* p_min = NULL, const void* p_max = NULL, const char* format = NULL, float power = 1.0f);
462 IMGUI_API bool DragScalarN(const char* label, ImGuiDataType data_type, void* p_data, int components, float v_speed, const void* p_min = NULL, const void* p_max = NULL, const char* format = NULL, float power = 1.0f);

576 // Popups, Modals
577 // The properties of popups windows are:
578 // - They block normal mouse hovering detection outside them. (*)
579 // - Unless modal, they can be closed by clicking anywhere outside them, or by pressing ESCAPE.
580 // - Their visibility state (~bool) is held internally by imgui instead of being held by the programmer as we are used to with regular Begin() calls.
581 // User can manipulate the visibility state by calling OpenPopup().
582 // - We default to use the right mouse (ImGuiMouseButton_Right=1) for the Popup Context functions.
583 // (*) You can use IsItemHovered(ImGuiHoveredFlags_AllowWhenBlockedByPopup) to bypass it and detect hovering even when normally blocked by a popup.
584 // Those three properties are connected. The library needs to hold their visibility state because it can close popups at any time.
585 IMGUI_API void OpenPopup(const char* str_id); // call to mark popup as open (don't call every frame!). popups are closed when user click outside, or if CloseCurrentPopup() is called within a BeginPopup()/EndPopup() block. By default, Selectable()/MenuItem() are calling CloseCurrentPopup(). Popup identifiers are relative to the current ID-stack (so OpenPopup and BeginPopup needs to be at the same level).
586 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopup(const char* str_id, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0); // return true if the popup is open, and you can start outputting to it. only call EndPopup() if BeginPopup() returns true!
587 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupContextItem(const char* str_id = NULL, ImGuiMouseButton mouse_button = 1); // helper to open and begin popup when clicked on last item. if you can pass a NULL str_id only if the previous item had an id. If you want to use that on a non-interactive item such as Text() you need to pass in an explicit ID here. read comments in .cpp!
588 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupContextWindow(const char* str_id = NULL, ImGuiMouseButton mouse_button = 1, bool also_over_items = true); // helper to open and begin popup when clicked on current window.
589 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupContextVoid(const char* str_id = NULL, ImGuiMouseButton mouse_button = 1); // helper to open and begin popup when clicked in void (where there are no imgui windows).
590 IMGUI_API bool BeginPopupModal(const char* name, bool* p_open = NULL, ImGuiWindowFlags flags = 0); // modal dialog (regular window with title bar, block interactions behind the modal window, can't close the modal window by clicking outside)
591 IMGUI_API void EndPopup(); // only call EndPopup() if BeginPopupXXX() returns true!
592 IMGUI_API bool OpenPopupOnItemClick(const char* str_id = NULL, ImGuiMouseButton mouse_button = 1); // helper to open popup when clicked on last item (note: actually triggers on the mouse _released_ event to be consistent with popup behaviors). return true when just opened.
593 IMGUI_API bool IsPopupOpen(const char* str_id); // return true if the popup is open at the current begin-ed level of the popup stack.
594 IMGUI_API void CloseCurrentPopup(); // close the popup we have begin-ed into. clicking on a MenuItem or Selectable automatically close the current popup.

606 IMGUI_API float GetColumnOffset(int column_index = -1); // get position of column line (in pixels, from the left side of the contents region). pass -1 to use current column, otherwise 0..GetColumnsCount() inclusive. column 0 is typically 0.0f

650 IMGUI_API bool IsItemFocused(); // is the last item focused for keyboard/gamepad navigation?
651 IMGUI_API bool IsItemClicked(ImGuiMouseButton mouse_button = 0); // is the last item clicked? (e.g. button/node just clicked on) == IsMouseClicked(mouse_button) && IsItemHovered()

653 IMGUI_API bool IsItemEdited(); // did the last item modify its underlying value this frame? or was pressed? This is generally the same as the "bool" return value of many widgets.
654 IMGUI_API bool IsItemActivated(); // was the last item just made active (item was previously inactive).
655 IMGUI_API bool IsItemDeactivated(); // was the last item just made inactive (item was previously active). Useful for Undo/Redo patterns with widgets that requires continuous editing.
656 IMGUI_API bool IsItemDeactivatedAfterEdit(); // was the last item just made inactive and made a value change when it was active? (e.g. Slider/Drag moved). Useful for Undo/Redo patterns with widgets that requires continuous editing. Note that you may get false positives (some widgets such as Combo()/ListBox()/Selectable() will return true even when clicking an already selected item).
657 IMGUI_API bool IsItemToggledOpen(); // was the last item open state toggled? set by TreeNode().
658 IMGUI_API bool IsAnyItemHovered(); // is any item hovered?
659 IMGUI_API bool IsAnyItemActive(); // is any item active?

695 IMGUI_API int GetKeyPressedAmount(int key_index, float repeat_delay, float rate); // uses provided repeat rate/delay. return a count, most often 0 or 1 but might be >1 if RepeatRate is small enough that DeltaTime > RepeatRate

This is equivalent to setting "io.WantCaptureKeyboard = want_capture_keyboard_value"; after the next NewFrame() call.

698 // Inputs Utilities: Mouse
699 // - To refer to a mouse button, you may use named enums in your code e.g. ImGuiMouseButton_Left, ImGuiMouseButton_Right.
700 // - You can also use regular integer: it is forever guaranteed that 0=Left, 1=Right, 2=Middle.
701 // - Dragging operations are only reported after mouse has moved a certain distance away from the initial clicking position (see 'lock_threshold' and 'io.MouseDraggingThreshold')
702 IMGUI_API bool IsMouseDown(ImGuiMouseButton button); // is mouse button held?
703 IMGUI_API bool IsMouseClicked(ImGuiMouseButton button, bool repeat = false); // did mouse button clicked? (went from !Down to Down)
704 IMGUI_API bool IsMouseReleased(ImGuiMouseButton button); // did mouse button released? (went from Down to !Down)
705 IMGUI_API bool IsMouseDoubleClicked(ImGuiMouseButton button); // did mouse button double-clicked? a double-click returns false in IsMouseClicked(). uses io.MouseDoubleClickTime.
706 IMGUI_API bool IsMouseHoveringRect(const ImVec2& r_min, const ImVec2& r_max, bool clip = true);// is mouse hovering given bounding rect (in screen space). clipped by current clipping settings, but disregarding of other consideration of focus/window ordering/popup-block.
707 IMGUI_API bool IsMousePosValid(const ImVec2* mouse_pos = NULL); // by convention we use (-FLT_MAX,-FLT_MAX) to denote that there is no mouse available
708 IMGUI_API bool IsAnyMouseDown(); // is any mouse button held?
709 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetMousePos(); // shortcut to ImGui::GetIO().MousePos provided by user, to be consistent with other calls
710 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetMousePosOnOpeningCurrentPopup(); // retrieve mouse position at the time of opening popup we have BeginPopup() into (helper to avoid user backing that value themselves)
711 IMGUI_API bool IsMouseDragging(ImGuiMouseButton button, float lock_threshold = -1.0f); // is mouse dragging? (if lock_threshold < -1.0f, uses io.MouseDraggingThreshold)
712 IMGUI_API ImVec2 GetMouseDragDelta(ImGuiMouseButton button = 0, float lock_threshold = -1.0f); // return the delta from the initial clicking position while the mouse button is pressed or was just released. This is locked and return 0.0f until the mouse moves past a distance threshold at least once (if lock_threshold < -1.0f, uses io.MouseDraggingThreshold)
713 IMGUI_API void ResetMouseDragDelta(ImGuiMouseButton button = 0); //
714 IMGUI_API ImGuiMouseCursor GetMouseCursor(); // get desired cursor type, reset in ImGui::NewFrame(), this is updated during the frame. valid before Render(). If you use software rendering by setting io.MouseDrawCursor ImGui will render those for you
715 IMGUI_API void SetMouseCursor(ImGuiMouseCursor cursor_type); // set desired cursor type
716 IMGUI_API void CaptureMouseFromApp(bool want_capture_mouse_value = true); // attention: misleading name! manually override io.WantCaptureMouse flag next frame (said flag is entirely left for your application to handle). This is equivalent to setting "io.WantCaptureMouse = want_capture_mouse_value;" after the next NewFrame() call.
717
718 // Clipboard Utilities (also see the LogToClipboard() function to capture or output text data to the clipboard)

722 // Settings/.Ini Utilities

728 IMGUI_API const char* SaveIniSettingsToMemory(size_t* out_ini_size = NULL); // return a zero-terminated string with the .ini data which you can save by your own mean. call when io.WantSaveIniSettings is set, then save data by your own mean and clear io.WantSaveIniSettings.

743// Flags for ImGui::Begin()
744enum ImGuiWindowFlags_
745{
746 ImGuiWindowFlags_None = 0,
747 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoTitleBar = 1 << 0, // Disable title-bar
748 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoResize = 1 << 1, // Disable user resizing with the lower-right grip
749 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoMove = 1 << 2, // Disable user moving the window
750 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoScrollbar = 1 << 3, // Disable scrollbars (window can still scroll with mouse or programmatically)
751 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoScrollWithMouse = 1 << 4, // Disable user vertically scrolling with mouse wheel. On child window, mouse wheel will be forwarded to the parent unless NoScrollbar is also set.
752 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoCollapse = 1 << 5, // Disable user collapsing window by double-clicking on it
753 ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysAutoResize = 1 << 6, // Resize every window to its content every frame
754 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoBackground = 1 << 7, // Disable drawing background color (WindowBg, etc.) and outside border. Similar as using SetNextWindowBgAlpha(0.0f).
755 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoSavedSettings = 1 << 8, // Never load/save settings in .ini file
756 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoMouseInputs = 1 << 9, // Disable catching mouse, hovering test with pass through.
757 ImGuiWindowFlags_MenuBar = 1 << 10, // Has a menu-bar
758 ImGuiWindowFlags_HorizontalScrollbar = 1 << 11, // Allow horizontal scrollbar to appear (off by default). You may use SetNextWindowContentSize(ImVec2(width,0.0f)); prior to calling Begin() to specify width. Read code in imgui_demo in the "Horizontal Scrolling" section.
759 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoFocusOnAppearing = 1 << 12, // Disable taking focus when transitioning from hidden to visible state
760 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoBringToFrontOnFocus = 1 << 13, // Disable bringing window to front when taking focus (e.g. clicking on it or programmatically giving it focus)
761 ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysVerticalScrollbar= 1 << 14, // Always show vertical scrollbar (even if ContentSize.y < Size.y)
762 ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysHorizontalScrollbar=1<< 15, // Always show horizontal scrollbar (even if ContentSize.x < Size.x)
763 ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysUseWindowPadding = 1 << 16, // Ensure child windows without border uses style.WindowPadding (ignored by default for non-bordered child windows, because more convenient)
764 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavInputs = 1 << 18, // No gamepad/keyboard navigation within the window
765 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavFocus = 1 << 19, // No focusing toward this window with gamepad/keyboard navigation (e.g. skipped by CTRL+TAB)
766 ImGuiWindowFlags_UnsavedDocument = 1 << 20, // Append '*' to title without affecting the ID, as a convenience to avoid using the ### operator. When used in a tab/docking context, tab is selected on closure and closure is deferred by one frame to allow code to cancel the closure (with a confirmation popup, etc.) without flicker.
767 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNav = ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavInputs | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavFocus,
768 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoDecoration = ImGuiWindowFlags_NoTitleBar | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoResize | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoScrollbar | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoCollapse,
769 ImGuiWindowFlags_NoInputs = ImGuiWindowFlags_NoMouseInputs | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavInputs | ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavFocus,
770
771 // [Internal]
772 ImGuiWindowFlags_NavFlattened = 1 << 23, // [BETA] Allow gamepad/keyboard navigation to cross over parent border to this child (only use on child that have no scrolling!)
773 ImGuiWindowFlags_ChildWindow = 1 << 24, // Don't use! For internal use by BeginChild()
774 ImGuiWindowFlags_Tooltip = 1 << 25, // Don't use! For internal use by BeginTooltip()
775 ImGuiWindowFlags_Popup = 1 << 26, // Don't use! For internal use by BeginPopup()
776 ImGuiWindowFlags_Modal = 1 << 27, // Don't use! For internal use by BeginPopupModal()
777 ImGuiWindowFlags_ChildMenu = 1 << 28 // Don't use! For internal use by BeginMenu()
778
779 // [Obsolete]
780 //ImGuiWindowFlags_ShowBorders = 1 << 7, // --> Set style.FrameBorderSize=1.0f or style.WindowBorderSize=1.0f to enable borders around items or windows.
781 //ImGuiWindowFlags_ResizeFromAnySide = 1 << 17, // --> Set io.ConfigWindowsResizeFromEdges=true and make sure mouse cursors are supported by back-end (io.BackendFlags & ImGuiBackendFlags_HasMouseCursors)
782};

784// Flags for ImGui::InputText()
785enum ImGuiInputTextFlags_
786{
787 ImGuiInputTextFlags_None = 0,
788 ImGuiInputTextFlags_CharsDecimal = 1 << 0, // Allow 0123456789.+-*/
789 ImGuiInputTextFlags_CharsHexadecimal = 1 << 1, // Allow 0123456789ABCDEFabcdef
790 ImGuiInputTextFlags_CharsUppercase = 1 << 2, // Turn a..z into A..Z
791 ImGuiInputTextFlags_CharsNoBlank = 1 << 3, // Filter out spaces, tabs
792 ImGuiInputTextFlags_AutoSelectAll = 1 << 4, // Select entire text when first taking mouse focus
793 ImGuiInputTextFlags_EnterReturnsTrue = 1 << 5, // Return 'true' when Enter is pressed (as opposed to every time the value was modified). Consider looking at the IsItemDeactivatedAfterEdit() function.
794 ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCompletion = 1 << 6, // Callback on pressing TAB (for completion handling)
795 ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackHistory = 1 << 7, // Callback on pressing Up/Down arrows (for history handling)
796 ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackAlways = 1 << 8, // Callback on each iteration. User code may query cursor position, modify text buffer.
797 ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCharFilter = 1 << 9, // Callback on character inputs to replace or discard them. Modify 'EventChar' to replace or discard, or return 1 in callback to discard.
798 ImGuiInputTextFlags_AllowTabInput = 1 << 10, // Pressing TAB input a '\t' character into the text field

990// Gamepad/Keyboard directional navigation
991// Keyboard: Set io.ConfigFlags |= ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableKeyboard to enable. NewFrame() will automatically fill io.NavInputs[] based on your io.KeysDown[] + io.KeyMap[] arrays.
992// Gamepad: Set io.ConfigFlags |= ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableGamepad to enable. Back-end: set ImGuiBackendFlags_HasGamepad and fill the io.NavInputs[] fields before calling NewFrame(). Note that io.NavInputs[] is cleared by EndFrame().
993// Read instructions in imgui.cpp for more details. Download PNG/PSD at http://goo.gl/9LgVZW.
994enum ImGuiNavInput_
995{
996 // Gamepad Mapping
997 ImGuiNavInput_Activate, // activate / open / toggle / tweak value // e.g. Cross (PS4), A (Xbox), A (Switch), Space (Keyboard)
998 ImGuiNavInput_Cancel, // cancel / close / exit // e.g. Circle (PS4), B (Xbox), B (Switch), Escape (Keyboard)
999 ImGuiNavInput_Input, // text input / on-screen keyboard // e.g. Triang.(PS4), Y (Xbox), X (Switch), Return (Keyboard)
1000 ImGuiNavInput_Menu, // tap: toggle menu / hold: focus, move, resize // e.g. Square (PS4), X (Xbox), Y (Switch), Alt (Keyboard)
1001 ImGuiNavInput_DpadLeft, // move / tweak / resize window (w/ PadMenu) // e.g. D-pad Left/Right/Up/Down (Gamepads), Arrow keys (Keyboard)
1002 ImGuiNavInput_DpadRight, //
1003 ImGuiNavInput_DpadUp, //
1004 ImGuiNavInput_DpadDown, //
1005 ImGuiNavInput_LStickLeft, // scroll / move window (w/ PadMenu) // e.g. Left Analog Stick Left/Right/Up/Down
1006 ImGuiNavInput_LStickRight, //
1007 ImGuiNavInput_LStickUp, //
1008 ImGuiNavInput_LStickDown, //
1009 ImGuiNavInput_FocusPrev, // next window (w/ PadMenu) // e.g. L1 or L2 (PS4), LB or LT (Xbox), L or ZL (Switch)
1010 ImGuiNavInput_FocusNext, // prev window (w/ PadMenu) // e.g. R1 or R2 (PS4), RB or RT (Xbox), R or ZL (Switch)
1011 ImGuiNavInput_TweakSlow, // slower tweaks // e.g. L1 or L2 (PS4), LB or LT (Xbox), L or ZL (Switch)
1012 ImGuiNavInput_TweakFast, // faster tweaks // e.g. R1 or R2 (PS4), RB or RT (Xbox), R or ZL (Switch)
1013
1014 // [Internal] Don't use directly! This is used internally to differentiate keyboard from gamepad inputs for behaviors that require to differentiate them.
1015 // Keyboard behavior that have no corresponding gamepad mapping (e.g. CTRL+TAB) will be directly reading from io.KeysDown[] instead of io.NavInputs[].
1016 ImGuiNavInput_KeyMenu_, // toggle menu // = io.KeyAlt
1017 ImGuiNavInput_KeyLeft_, // move left // = Arrow keys
1018 ImGuiNavInput_KeyRight_, // move right
1019 ImGuiNavInput_KeyUp_, // move up
1020 ImGuiNavInput_KeyDown_, // move down
1021 ImGuiNavInput_COUNT,
1022 ImGuiNavInput_InternalStart_ = ImGuiNavInput_KeyMenu_
1023};

1025// Configuration flags stored in io.ConfigFlags. Set by user/application.
1026enum ImGuiConfigFlags_
1027{
1028 ImGuiConfigFlags_None = 0,
1029 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableKeyboard = 1 << 0, // Master keyboard navigation enable flag. NewFrame() will automatically fill io.NavInputs[] based on io.KeysDown[].
1030 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableGamepad = 1 << 1, // Master gamepad navigation enable flag. This is mostly to instruct your imgui back-end to fill io.NavInputs[]. Back-end also needs to set ImGuiBackendFlags_HasGamepad.
1031 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableSetMousePos = 1 << 2, // Instruct navigation to move the mouse cursor. May be useful on TV/console systems where moving a virtual mouse is awkward. Will update io.MousePos and set io.WantSetMousePos=true. If enabled you MUST honor io.WantSetMousePos requests in your binding, otherwise ImGui will react as if the mouse is jumping around back and forth.
1032 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavNoCaptureKeyboard = 1 << 3, // Instruct navigation to not set the io.WantCaptureKeyboard flag when io.NavActive is set.
1033 ImGuiConfigFlags_NoMouse = 1 << 4, // Instruct imgui to clear mouse position/buttons in NewFrame(). This allows ignoring the mouse information set by the back-end.
1034 ImGuiConfigFlags_NoMouseCursorChange = 1 << 5, // Instruct back-end to not alter mouse cursor shape and visibility. Use if the back-end cursor changes are interfering with yours and you don't want to use SetMouseCursor() to change mouse cursor. You may want to honor requests from imgui by reading GetMouseCursor() yourself instead.
1035
1036 // User storage (to allow your back-end/engine to communicate to code that may be shared between multiple projects. Those flags are not used by core Dear ImGui)
1037 ImGuiConfigFlags_IsSRGB = 1 << 20, // Application is SRGB-aware.
1038 ImGuiConfigFlags_IsTouchScreen = 1 << 21 // Application is using a touch screen instead of a mouse.
1039};

1047 ImGuiBackendFlags_HasSetMousePos = 1 << 2, // Back-end Platform supports io.WantSetMousePos requests to reposition the OS mouse position (only used if ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableSetMousePos is set).

1163 // User Options (right-click on widget to change some of them).
1164 ImGuiColorEditFlags_AlphaBar = 1 << 16, // // ColorEdit, ColorPicker: show vertical alpha bar/gradient in picker.
1165 ImGuiColorEditFlags_AlphaPreview = 1 << 17, // // ColorEdit, ColorPicker, ColorButton: display preview as a transparent color over a checkerboard, instead of opaque.
1166 ImGuiColorEditFlags_AlphaPreviewHalf= 1 << 18, // // ColorEdit, ColorPicker, ColorButton: display half opaque / half checkerboard, instead of opaque.
1167 ImGuiColorEditFlags_HDR = 1 << 19, // // (WIP) ColorEdit: Currently only disable 0.0f..1.0f limits in RGBA edition (note: you probably want to use ImGuiColorEditFlags_Float flag as well).
1168 ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayRGB = 1 << 20, // [Display] // ColorEdit: override _display_ type among RGB/HSV/Hex. ColorPicker: select any combination using one or more of RGB/HSV/Hex.
1169 ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHSV = 1 << 21, // [Display] // "
1170 ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHex = 1 << 22, // [Display] // "
1171 ImGuiColorEditFlags_Uint8 = 1 << 23, // [DataType] // ColorEdit, ColorPicker, ColorButton: _display_ values formatted as 0..255.
1172 ImGuiColorEditFlags_Float = 1 << 24, // [DataType] // ColorEdit, ColorPicker, ColorButton: _display_ values formatted as 0.0f..1.0f floats instead of 0..255 integers. No round-trip of value via integers.
1173 ImGuiColorEditFlags_PickerHueBar = 1 << 25, // [Picker] // ColorPicker: bar for Hue, rectangle for Sat/Value.
1174 ImGuiColorEditFlags_PickerHueWheel = 1 << 26, // [Picker] // ColorPicker: wheel for Hue, triangle for Sat/Value.
1175 ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputRGB = 1 << 27, // [Input] // ColorEdit, ColorPicker: input and output data in RGB format.
1176 ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputHSV = 1 << 28, // [Input] // ColorEdit, ColorPicker: input and output data in HSV format.
1177
1178 // Defaults Options. You can set application defaults using SetColorEditOptions(). The intent is that you probably don't want to
1179 // override them in most of your calls. Let the user choose via the option menu and/or call SetColorEditOptions() once during startup.
1180 ImGuiColorEditFlags__OptionsDefault = ImGuiColorEditFlags_Uint8|ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayRGB|ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputRGB|ImGuiColorEditFlags_PickerHueBar,
1181
1182 // [Internal] Masks

1186 ImGuiColorEditFlags__InputMask = ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputRGB|ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputHSV
1187
1188 // Obsolete names (will be removed)
1189#ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
1190 , ImGuiColorEditFlags_RGB = ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayRGB, ImGuiColorEditFlags_HSV = ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHSV, ImGuiColorEditFlags_HEX = ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHex // [renamed in 1.69]
1191#endif

1226// Enumeration for ImGui::SetWindow***(), SetNextWindow***(), SetNextItem***() functions
1227// Represent a condition.
1228// Important: Treat as a regular enum! Do NOT combine multiple values using binary operators! All the functions above treat 0 as a shortcut to ImGuiCond_Always.
1229enum ImGuiCond_
1230{
1231 ImGuiCond_Always = 1 << 0, // Set the variable
1232 ImGuiCond_Once = 1 << 1, // Set the variable once per runtime session (only the first call with succeed)
1233 ImGuiCond_FirstUseEver = 1 << 2, // Set the variable if the object/window has no persistently saved data (no entry in .ini file)
1234 ImGuiCond_Appearing = 1 << 3 // Set the variable if the object/window is appearing after being hidden/inactive (or the first time)
1235};

1237//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1238// Helpers: Memory allocations macros
1239// IM_MALLOC(), IM_FREE(), IM_NEW(), IM_PLACEMENT_NEW(), IM_DELETE()
1240// We call C++ constructor on own allocated memory via the placement "new(ptr) Type()" syntax.
1241// Defining a custom placement new() with a dummy parameter allows us to bypass including <new> which on some platforms complains when user has disabled exceptions.
1242//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1243
1244struct ImNewDummy {};
1245inline void* operator new(size_t, ImNewDummy, void* ptr) { return ptr; }
1246inline void operator delete(void*, ImNewDummy, void*) {} // This is only required so we can use the symmetrical new()
1247#define IM_ALLOC(_SIZE) ImGui::MemAlloc(_SIZE)
1248#define IM_FREE(_PTR) ImGui::MemFree(_PTR)
1249#define IM_PLACEMENT_NEW(_PTR) new(ImNewDummy(), _PTR)
1250#define IM_NEW(_TYPE) new(ImNewDummy(), ImGui::MemAlloc(sizeof(_TYPE))) _TYPE
1251template<typename T> void IM_DELETE(T* p) { if (p) { p->~T(); ImGui::MemFree(p); } }
1252
1253//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1254// Helper: ImVector<>
1255// Lightweight std::vector<>-like class to avoid dragging dependencies (also, some implementations of STL with debug enabled are absurdly slow, we bypass it so our code runs fast in debug).
1256//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1257// - You generally do NOT need to care or use this ever. But we need to make it available in imgui.h because some of our public structures are relying on it.
1258// - We use std-like naming convention here, which is a little unusual for this codebase.
1259// - Important: clear() frees memory, resize(0) keep the allocated buffer. We use resize(0) a lot to intentionally recycle allocated buffers across frames and amortize our costs.
1260// - Important: our implementation does NOT call C++ constructors/destructors, we treat everything as raw data! This is intentional but be extra mindful of that,
1261// Do NOT use this class as a std::vector replacement in your own code! Many of the structures used by dear imgui can be safely initialized by a zero-memset.
1262//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1263
1264template<typename T>
1265struct ImVector
1266{
1267 int Size;
1268 int Capacity;
1269 T* Data;
1270
1271 // Provide standard typedefs but we don't use them ourselves.
1272 typedef T value_type;
1273 typedef value_type* iterator;
1274 typedef const value_type* const_iterator;
1275
1276 // Constructors, destructor
1277 inline ImVector() { Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; }
1278 inline ImVector(const ImVector<T>& src) { Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; operator=(src); }
1279 inline ImVector<T>& operator=(const ImVector<T>& src) { clear(); resize(src.Size); memcpy(Data, src.Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(T)); return *this; }
1280 inline ~ImVector() { if (Data) IM_FREE(Data); }
1281
1282 inline bool empty() const { return Size == 0; }
1283 inline int size() const { return Size; }
1284 inline int size_in_bytes() const { return Size * (int)sizeof(T); }
1285 inline int capacity() const { return Capacity; }
1286 inline T& operator[](int i) { IM_ASSERT(i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1287 inline const T& operator[](int i) const { IM_ASSERT(i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1288
1289 inline void clear() { if (Data) { Size = Capacity = 0; IM_FREE(Data); Data = NULL; } }
1290 inline T* begin() { return Data; }
1291 inline const T* begin() const { return Data; }
1292 inline T* end() { return Data + Size; }
1293 inline const T* end() const { return Data + Size; }
1294 inline T& front() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1295 inline const T& front() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1296 inline T& back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1297 inline const T& back() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1298 inline void swap(ImVector<T>& rhs) { int rhs_size = rhs.Size; rhs.Size = Size; Size = rhs_size; int rhs_cap = rhs.Capacity; rhs.Capacity = Capacity; Capacity = rhs_cap; T* rhs_data = rhs.Data; rhs.Data = Data; Data = rhs_data; }
1299
1300 inline int _grow_capacity(int sz) const { int new_capacity = Capacity ? (Capacity + Capacity/2) : 8; return new_capacity > sz ? new_capacity : sz; }
1301 inline void resize(int new_size) { if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); Size = new_size; }
1302 inline void resize(int new_size, const T& v) { if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); if (new_size > Size) for (int n = Size; n < new_size; n++) memcpy(&Data[n], &v, sizeof(v)); Size = new_size; }
1303 inline void shrink(int new_size) { IM_ASSERT(new_size <= Size); Size = new_size; } // Resize a vector to a smaller size, guaranteed not to cause a reallocation
1304 inline void reserve(int new_capacity) { if (new_capacity <= Capacity) return; T* new_data = (T*)IM_ALLOC((size_t)new_capacity * sizeof(T)); if (Data) { memcpy(new_data, Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(T)); IM_FREE(Data); } Data = new_data; Capacity = new_capacity; }
1305
1306 // NB: It is illegal to call push_back/push_front/insert with a reference pointing inside the ImVector data itself! e.g. v.push_back(v[10]) is forbidden.
1307 inline void push_back(const T& v) { if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); memcpy(&Data[Size], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++; }
1308 inline void pop_back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); Size--; }
1309 inline void push_front(const T& v) { if (Size == 0) push_back(v); else insert(Data, v); }
1310 inline T* erase(const T* it) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data+Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + 1, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - 1) * sizeof(T)); Size--; return Data + off; }
1311 inline T* erase(const T* it, const T* it_last){ IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data+Size && it_last > it && it_last <= Data+Size); const ptrdiff_t count = it_last - it; const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + count, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - count) * sizeof(T)); Size -= (int)count; return Data + off; }
1312 inline T* erase_unsorted(const T* it) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data+Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (it < Data+Size-1) memcpy(Data + off, Data + Size - 1, sizeof(T)); Size--; return Data + off; }
1313 inline T* insert(const T* it, const T& v) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it <= Data+Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); if (off < (int)Size) memmove(Data + off + 1, Data + off, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off) * sizeof(T)); memcpy(&Data[off], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++; return Data + off; }
1314 inline bool contains(const T& v) const { const T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data++ == v) return true; return false; }
1315 inline T* find(const T& v) { T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data == v) break; else ++data; return data; }
1316 inline const T* find(const T& v) const { const T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data == v) break; else ++data; return data; }
1317 inline bool find_erase(const T& v) { const T* it = find(v); if (it < Data + Size) { erase(it); return true; } return false; }
1318 inline bool find_erase_unsorted(const T& v) { const T* it = find(v); if (it < Data + Size) { erase_unsorted(it); return true; } return false; }
1319 inline int index_from_ptr(const T* it) const { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; return (int)off; }
1320};

1322//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1323// ImGuiStyle
1324// You may modify the ImGui::GetStyle() main instance during initialization and before NewFrame().
1325// During the frame, use ImGui::PushStyleVar(ImGuiStyleVar_XXXX)/PopStyleVar() to alter the main style values,
1326// and ImGui::PushStyleColor(ImGuiCol_XXX)/PopStyleColor() for colors.
1327//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1328
1329struct ImGuiStyle
1330{
1331 float Alpha; // Global alpha applies to everything in Dear ImGui.
1332 ImVec2 WindowPadding; // Padding within a window.
1333 float WindowRounding; // Radius of window corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular windows.
1334 float WindowBorderSize; // Thickness of border around windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1335 ImVec2 WindowMinSize; // Minimum window size. This is a global setting. If you want to constraint individual windows, use SetNextWindowSizeConstraints().
1336 ImVec2 WindowTitleAlign; // Alignment for title bar text. Defaults to (0.0f,0.5f) for left-aligned,vertically centered.
1337 ImGuiDir WindowMenuButtonPosition; // Side of the collapsing/docking button in the title bar (None/Left/Right). Defaults to ImGuiDir_Left.
1338 float ChildRounding; // Radius of child window corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular windows.
1339 float ChildBorderSize; // Thickness of border around child windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1340 float PopupRounding; // Radius of popup window corners rounding. (Note that tooltip windows use WindowRounding)
1341 float PopupBorderSize; // Thickness of border around popup/tooltip windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1342 ImVec2 FramePadding; // Padding within a framed rectangle (used by most widgets).
1343 float FrameRounding; // Radius of frame corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular frame (used by most widgets).
1344 float FrameBorderSize; // Thickness of border around frames. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1345 ImVec2 ItemSpacing; // Horizontal and vertical spacing between widgets/lines.
1346 ImVec2 ItemInnerSpacing; // Horizontal and vertical spacing between within elements of a composed widget (e.g. a slider and its label).
1347 ImVec2 TouchExtraPadding; // Expand reactive bounding box for touch-based system where touch position is not accurate enough. Unfortunately we don't sort widgets so priority on overlap will always be given to the first widget. So don't grow this too much!
1348 float IndentSpacing; // Horizontal indentation when e.g. entering a tree node. Generally == (FontSize + FramePadding.x*2).
1349 float ColumnsMinSpacing; // Minimum horizontal spacing between two columns. Preferably > (FramePadding.x + 1).
1350 float ScrollbarSize; // Width of the vertical scrollbar, Height of the horizontal scrollbar.
1351 float ScrollbarRounding; // Radius of grab corners for scrollbar.
1352 float GrabMinSize; // Minimum width/height of a grab box for slider/scrollbar.
1353 float GrabRounding; // Radius of grabs corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular slider grabs.
1354 float TabRounding; // Radius of upper corners of a tab. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular tabs.
1355 float TabBorderSize; // Thickness of border around tabs.
1356 ImGuiDir ColorButtonPosition; // Side of the color button in the ColorEdit4 widget (left/right). Defaults to ImGuiDir_Right.
1357 ImVec2 ButtonTextAlign; // Alignment of button text when button is larger than text. Defaults to (0.5f, 0.5f) (centered).
1358 ImVec2 SelectableTextAlign; // Alignment of selectable text when selectable is larger than text. Defaults to (0.0f, 0.0f) (top-left aligned).
1359 ImVec2 DisplayWindowPadding; // Window position are clamped to be visible within the display area by at least this amount. Only applies to regular windows.
1360 ImVec2 DisplaySafeAreaPadding; // If you cannot see the edges of your screen (e.g. on a TV) increase the safe area padding. Apply to popups/tooltips as well regular windows. NB: Prefer configuring your TV sets correctly!
1361 float MouseCursorScale; // Scale software rendered mouse cursor (when io.MouseDrawCursor is enabled). May be removed later.
1362 bool AntiAliasedLines; // Enable anti-aliasing on lines/borders. Disable if you are really tight on CPU/GPU.
1363 bool AntiAliasedFill; // Enable anti-aliasing on filled shapes (rounded rectangles, circles, etc.)
1364 float CurveTessellationTol; // Tessellation tolerance when using PathBezierCurveTo() without a specific number of segments. Decrease for highly tessellated curves (higher quality, more polygons), increase to reduce quality.
1365 float CircleSegmentMaxError; // Maximum error (in pixels) allowed when using AddCircle()/AddCircleFilled() or drawing rounded corner rectangles with no explicit segment count specified. Decrease for higher quality but more geometry.
1366 ImVec4 Colors[ImGuiCol_COUNT];
1367
1368 IMGUI_API ImGuiStyle();
1369 IMGUI_API void ScaleAllSizes(float scale_factor);
1370};

1473 bool WantSaveIniSettings; // When manual .ini load/save is active (io.IniFilename == NULL), this will be set to notify your application that you can call SaveIniSettingsToMemory() and save yourself. IMPORTANT: You need to clear io.WantSaveIniSettings yourself.
1474 bool NavActive; // Directional navigation is currently allowed (will handle ImGuiKey_NavXXX events) = a window is focused and it doesn't use the ImGuiWindowFlags_NoNavInputs flag.
1475 bool NavVisible; // Directional navigation is visible and allowed (will handle ImGuiKey_NavXXX events).
1476 float Framerate; // Application framerate estimation, in frame per second. Solely for convenience. Rolling average estimation based on IO.DeltaTime over 120 frames

1478 int MetricsRenderIndices; // Indices output during last call to Render() = number of triangles * 3
1479 int MetricsRenderWindows; // Number of visible windows
1480 int MetricsActiveWindows; // Number of active windows
1481 int MetricsActiveAllocations; // Number of active allocations, updated by MemAlloc/MemFree based on current context. May be off if you have multiple imgui contexts.
1482 ImVec2 MouseDelta; // Mouse delta. Note that this is zero if either current or previous position are invalid (-FLT_MAX,-FLT_MAX), so a disappearing/reappearing mouse won't have a huge delta.

1513// Shared state of InputText(), passed as an argument to your callback when a ImGuiInputTextFlags_Callback* flag is used.
1514// The callback function should return 0 by default.
1515// Callbacks (follow a flag name and see comments in ImGuiInputTextFlags_ declarations for more details)
1516// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCompletion: Callback on pressing TAB
1517// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackHistory: Callback on pressing Up/Down arrows
1518// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackAlways: Callback on each iteration
1519// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCharFilter: Callback on character inputs to replace or discard them. Modify 'EventChar' to replace or discard, or return 1 in callback to discard.
1520// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackResize: Callback on buffer capacity changes request (beyond 'buf_size' parameter value), allowing the string to grow.
1521struct ImGuiInputTextCallbackData
1522{
1523 ImGuiInputTextFlags EventFlag; // One ImGuiInputTextFlags_Callback* // Read-only
1524 ImGuiInputTextFlags Flags; // What user passed to InputText() // Read-only
1525 void* UserData; // What user passed to InputText() // Read-only
1526
1527 // Arguments for the different callback events
1528 // - To modify the text buffer in a callback, prefer using the InsertChars() / DeleteChars() function. InsertChars() will take care of calling the resize callback if necessary.
1529 // - If you know your edits are not going to resize the underlying buffer allocation, you may modify the contents of 'Buf[]' directly. You need to update 'BufTextLen' accordingly (0 <= BufTextLen < BufSize) and set 'BufDirty'' to true so InputText can update its internal state.
1530 ImWchar EventChar; // Character input // Read-write // [CharFilter] Replace character with another one, or set to zero to drop. return 1 is equivalent to setting EventChar=0;
1531 ImGuiKey EventKey; // Key pressed (Up/Down/TAB) // Read-only // [Completion,History]
1532 char* Buf; // Text buffer // Read-write // [Resize] Can replace pointer / [Completion,History,Always] Only write to pointed data, don't replace the actual pointer!
1533 int BufTextLen; // Text length (in bytes) // Read-write // [Resize,Completion,History,Always] Exclude zero-terminator storage. In C land: == strlen(some_text), in C++ land: string.length()
1534 int BufSize; // Buffer size (in bytes) = capacity+1 // Read-only // [Resize,Completion,History,Always] Include zero-terminator storage. In C land == ARRAYSIZE(my_char_array), in C++ land: string.capacity()+1
1535 bool BufDirty; // Set if you modify Buf/BufTextLen! // Write // [Completion,History,Always]
1536 int CursorPos; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always]
1537 int SelectionStart; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always] == to SelectionEnd when no selection)
1538 int SelectionEnd; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always]
1539
1540 // Helper functions for text manipulation.
1541 // Use those function to benefit from the CallbackResize behaviors. Calling those function reset the selection.
1542 IMGUI_API ImGuiInputTextCallbackData();
1543 IMGUI_API void DeleteChars(int pos, int bytes_count);
1544 IMGUI_API void InsertChars(int pos, const char* text, const char* text_end = NULL);
1545 bool HasSelection() const { return SelectionStart != SelectionEnd; }
1546};

1549// NB: For basic min/max size constraint on each axis you don't need to use the callback! The SetNextWindowSizeConstraints() parameters are enough.
1550struct ImGuiSizeCallbackData
1551{

1553 ImVec2 Pos; // Read-only. Window position, for reference.
1554 ImVec2 CurrentSize; // Read-only. Current window size.
1555 ImVec2 DesiredSize; // Read-write. Desired size, based on user's mouse position. Write to this field to restrain resizing.

1618// Helper: Execute a block of code at maximum once a frame. Convenient if you want to quickly create an UI within deep-nested code that runs multiple times every frame.
1619// Usage: static ImGuiOnceUponAFrame oaf; if (oaf) ImGui::Text("This will be called only once per frame");
1620struct ImGuiOnceUponAFrame
1621{
1622 ImGuiOnceUponAFrame() { RefFrame = -1; }
1623 mutable int RefFrame;
1624 operator bool() const { int current_frame = ImGui::GetFrameCount(); if (RefFrame == current_frame) return false; RefFrame = current_frame; return true; }
1625};

1653// Helper: Growable text buffer for logging/accumulating text
1654// (this could be called 'ImGuiTextBuilder' / 'ImGuiStringBuilder')
1655struct ImGuiTextBuffer
1656{
1657 ImVector<char> Buf;
1658 IMGUI_API static char EmptyString[1];
1659
1660 ImGuiTextBuffer() { }
1661 inline char operator[](int i) const { IM_ASSERT(Buf.Data != NULL); return Buf.Data[i]; }
1662 const char* begin() const { return Buf.Data ? &Buf.front() : EmptyString; }
1663 const char* end() const { return Buf.Data ? &Buf.back() : EmptyString; } // Buf is zero-terminated, so end() will point on the zero-terminator
1664 int size() const { return Buf.Size ? Buf.Size - 1 : 0; }
1665 bool empty() const { return Buf.Size <= 1; }
1666 void clear() { Buf.clear(); }
1667 void reserve(int capacity) { Buf.reserve(capacity); }
1668 const char* c_str() const { return Buf.Data ? Buf.Data : EmptyString; }
1669 IMGUI_API void append(const char* str, const char* str_end = NULL);
1670 IMGUI_API void appendf(const char* fmt, ...) IM_FMTARGS(2);
1671 IMGUI_API void appendfv(const char* fmt, va_list args) IM_FMTLIST(2);

1674// Helper: Key->Value storage
1675// Typically you don't have to worry about this since a storage is held within each Window.
1676// We use it to e.g. store collapse state for a tree (Int 0/1)
1677// This is optimized for efficient lookup (dichotomy into a contiguous buffer) and rare insertion (typically tied to user interactions aka max once a frame)
1678// You can use it as custom user storage for temporary values. Declare your own storage if, for example:
1679// - You want to manipulate the open/close state of a particular sub-tree in your interface (tree node uses Int 0/1 to store their state).
1680// - You want to store custom debug data easily without adding or editing structures in your code (probably not efficient, but convenient)
1681// Types are NOT stored, so it is up to you to make sure your Key don't collide with different types.
1682struct ImGuiStorage
1683{
1684 // [Internal]
1685 struct ImGuiStoragePair
1686 {
1687 ImGuiID key;
1688 union { int val_i; float val_f; void* val_p; };
1689 ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, int _val_i) { key = _key; val_i = _val_i; }
1690 ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, float _val_f) { key = _key; val_f = _val_f; }
1691 ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, void* _val_p) { key = _key; val_p = _val_p; }
1692 };
1693
1694 ImVector<ImGuiStoragePair> Data;
1695
1696 // - Get***() functions find pair, never add/allocate. Pairs are sorted so a query is O(log N)
1697 // - Set***() functions find pair, insertion on demand if missing.
1698 // - Sorted insertion is costly, paid once. A typical frame shouldn't need to insert any new pair.
1699 void Clear() { Data.clear(); }
1700 IMGUI_API int GetInt(ImGuiID key, int default_val = 0) const;
1701 IMGUI_API void SetInt(ImGuiID key, int val);
1702 IMGUI_API bool GetBool(ImGuiID key, bool default_val = false) const;
1703 IMGUI_API void SetBool(ImGuiID key, bool val);
1704 IMGUI_API float GetFloat(ImGuiID key, float default_val = 0.0f) const;
1705 IMGUI_API void SetFloat(ImGuiID key, float val);
1706 IMGUI_API void* GetVoidPtr(ImGuiID key) const; // default_val is NULL
1707 IMGUI_API void SetVoidPtr(ImGuiID key, void* val);
1708
1709 // - Get***Ref() functions finds pair, insert on demand if missing, return pointer. Useful if you intend to do Get+Set.
1710 // - References are only valid until a new value is added to the storage. Calling a Set***() function or a Get***Ref() function invalidates the pointer.
1711 // - A typical use case where this is convenient for quick hacking (e.g. add storage during a live Edit&Continue session if you can't modify existing struct)
1712 // float* pvar = ImGui::GetFloatRef(key); ImGui::SliderFloat("var", pvar, 0, 100.0f); some_var += *pvar;
1713 IMGUI_API int* GetIntRef(ImGuiID key, int default_val = 0);
1714 IMGUI_API bool* GetBoolRef(ImGuiID key, bool default_val = false);
1715 IMGUI_API float* GetFloatRef(ImGuiID key, float default_val = 0.0f);
1716 IMGUI_API void** GetVoidPtrRef(ImGuiID key, void* default_val = NULL);
1717
1718 // Use on your own storage if you know only integer are being stored (open/close all tree nodes)
1719 IMGUI_API void SetAllInt(int val);
1720
1721 // For quicker full rebuild of a storage (instead of an incremental one), you may add all your contents and then sort once.
1722 IMGUI_API void BuildSortByKey();
1723};
