1725// Helper: Manually clip large list of items.
1726// If you are submitting lots of evenly spaced items and you have a random access to the list, you can perform coarse clipping based on visibility to save yourself from processing those items at all.
1727// The clipper calculates the range of visible items and advance the cursor to compensate for the non-visible items we have skipped.
1728// ImGui already clip items based on their bounds but it needs to measure text size to do so. Coarse clipping before submission makes this cost and your own data fetching/submission cost null.
1729// Usage:
1730// ImGuiListClipper clipper(1000); // we have 1000 elements, evenly spaced.
1731// while (clipper.Step())
1732// for (int i = clipper.DisplayStart; i < clipper.DisplayEnd; i++)
1733// ImGui::Text("line number %d", i);
1734// - Step 0: the clipper let you process the first element, regardless of it being visible or not, so we can measure the element height (step skipped if we passed a known height as second arg to constructor).
1735// - Step 1: the clipper infer height from first element, calculate the actual range of elements to display, and position the cursor before the first element.
1736// - (Step 2: dummy step only required if an explicit items_height was passed to constructor or Begin() and user call Step(). Does nothing and switch to Step 3.)
1737// - Step 3: the clipper validate that we have reached the expected Y position (corresponding to element DisplayEnd), advance the cursor to the end of the list and then returns 'false' to end the loop.
1738struct ImGuiListClipper
1739{
1740 int DisplayStart, DisplayEnd;
1741 int ItemsCount;
1742
1743 // [Internal]
1744 int StepNo;
1745 float ItemsHeight;
1746 float StartPosY;
1747
1748 // items_count: Use -1 to ignore (you can call Begin later). Use INT_MAX if you don't know how many items you have (in which case the cursor won't be advanced in the final step).
1749 // items_height: Use -1.0f to be calculated automatically on first step. Otherwise pass in the distance between your items, typically GetTextLineHeightWithSpacing() or GetFrameHeightWithSpacing().
1750 // If you don't specify an items_height, you NEED to call Step(). If you specify items_height you may call the old Begin()/End() api directly, but prefer calling Step().
1751 ImGuiListClipper(int items_count = -1, float items_height = -1.0f) { Begin(items_count, items_height); } // NB: Begin() initialize every fields (as we allow user to call Begin/End multiple times on a same instance if they want).
1752 ~ImGuiListClipper() { IM_ASSERT(ItemsCount == -1); } // Assert if user forgot to call End() or Step() until false.
1753
1754 IMGUI_API bool Step(); // Call until it returns false. The DisplayStart/DisplayEnd fields will be set and you can process/draw those items.
1755 IMGUI_API void Begin(int items_count, float items_height = -1.0f); // Automatically called by constructor if you passed 'items_count' or by Step() in Step 1.
1756 IMGUI_API void End(); // Automatically called on the last call of Step() that returns false.
1757};
1758
1759// Helpers macros to generate 32-bit encoded colors
1760#ifdef IMGUI_USE_BGRA_PACKED_COLOR
1761#define IM_COL32_R_SHIFT 16
1762#define IM_COL32_G_SHIFT 8
1763#define IM_COL32_B_SHIFT 0
1764#define IM_COL32_A_SHIFT 24
1765#define IM_COL32_A_MASK 0xFF000000
1766#else
1767#define IM_COL32_R_SHIFT 0
1768#define IM_COL32_G_SHIFT 8
1769#define IM_COL32_B_SHIFT 16
1770#define IM_COL32_A_SHIFT 24
1771#define IM_COL32_A_MASK 0xFF000000
1772#endif
1773#define IM_COL32(R,G,B,A) (((ImU32)(A)<<IM_COL32_A_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(B)<<IM_COL32_B_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(G)<<IM_COL32_G_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(R)<<IM_COL32_R_SHIFT))
1774#define IM_COL32_WHITE IM_COL32(255,255,255,255) // Opaque white = 0xFFFFFFFF
1775#define IM_COL32_BLACK IM_COL32(0,0,0,255) // Opaque black
1776#define IM_COL32_BLACK_TRANS IM_COL32(0,0,0,0) // Transparent black = 0x00000000
1777
1778// Helper: ImColor() implicitly converts colors to either ImU32 (packed 4x1 byte) or ImVec4 (4x1 float)
1779// Prefer using IM_COL32() macros if you want a guaranteed compile-time ImU32 for usage with ImDrawList API.
1780// **Avoid storing ImColor! Store either u32 of ImVec4. This is not a full-featured color class. MAY OBSOLETE.
1781// **None of the ImGui API are using ImColor directly but you can use it as a convenience to pass colors in either ImU32 or ImVec4 formats. Explicitly cast to ImU32 or ImVec4 if needed.
1782struct ImColor
1783{
1784 ImVec4 Value;
1785
1786 ImColor() { Value.x = Value.y = Value.z = Value.w = 0.0f; }
1787 ImColor(int r, int g, int b, int a = 255) { float sc = 1.0f/255.0f; Value.x = (float)r * sc; Value.y = (float)g * sc; Value.z = (float)b * sc; Value.w = (float)a * sc; }
1788 ImColor(ImU32 rgba) { float sc = 1.0f/255.0f; Value.x = (float)((rgba>>IM_COL32_R_SHIFT)&0xFF) * sc; Value.y = (float)((rgba>>IM_COL32_G_SHIFT)&0xFF) * sc; Value.z = (float)((rgba>>IM_COL32_B_SHIFT)&0xFF) * sc; Value.w = (float)((rgba>>IM_COL32_A_SHIFT)&0xFF) * sc; }
1789 ImColor(float r, float g, float b, float a = 1.0f) { Value.x = r; Value.y = g; Value.z = b; Value.w = a; }
1790 ImColor(const ImVec4& col) { Value = col; }
1791 inline operator ImU32() const { return ImGui::ColorConvertFloat4ToU32(Value); }
1792 inline operator ImVec4() const { return Value; }
1793
1794 // FIXME-OBSOLETE: May need to obsolete/cleanup those helpers.
1795 inline void SetHSV(float h, float s, float v, float a = 1.0f){ ImGui::ColorConvertHSVtoRGB(h, s, v, Value.x, Value.y, Value.z); Value.w = a; }
1796 static ImColor HSV(float h, float s, float v, float a = 1.0f) { float r,g,b; ImGui::ColorConvertHSVtoRGB(h, s, v, r, g, b); return ImColor(r,g,b,a); }
1797};

1799//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1800// Draw List API (ImDrawCmd, ImDrawIdx, ImDrawVert, ImDrawChannel, ImDrawListSplitter, ImDrawListFlags, ImDrawList, ImDrawData)
1801// Hold a series of drawing commands. The user provides a renderer for ImDrawData which essentially contains an array of ImDrawList.
1802//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1803
1804// Draw callbacks for advanced uses.
1805// NB: You most likely do NOT need to use draw callbacks just to create your own widget or customized UI rendering,
1806// you can poke into the draw list for that! Draw callback may be useful for example to:
1807// A) Change your GPU render state,
1808// B) render a complex 3D scene inside a UI element without an intermediate texture/render target, etc.
1809// The expected behavior from your rendering function is 'if (cmd.UserCallback != NULL) { cmd.UserCallback(parent_list, cmd); } else { RenderTriangles() }'
1810// If you want to override the signature of ImDrawCallback, you can simply use e.g. '#define ImDrawCallback MyDrawCallback' (in imconfig.h) + update rendering back-end accordingly.
1811#ifndef ImDrawCallback
1812typedef void (*ImDrawCallback)(const ImDrawList* parent_list, const ImDrawCmd* cmd);
1813#endif
1814
1815// Special Draw callback value to request renderer back-end to reset the graphics/render state.
1816// The renderer back-end needs to handle this special value, otherwise it will crash trying to call a function at this address.
1817// This is useful for example if you submitted callbacks which you know have altered the render state and you want it to be restored.
1818// It is not done by default because they are many perfectly useful way of altering render state for imgui contents (e.g. changing shader/blending settings before an Image call).
1819#define ImDrawCallback_ResetRenderState (ImDrawCallback)(-1)
1820
1821// Typically, 1 command = 1 GPU draw call (unless command is a callback)
1822// Pre 1.71 back-ends will typically ignore the VtxOffset/IdxOffset fields. When 'io.BackendFlags & ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset'
1823// is enabled, those fields allow us to render meshes larger than 64K vertices while keeping 16-bit indices.
1824struct ImDrawCmd
1825{
1826 unsigned int ElemCount; // Number of indices (multiple of 3) to be rendered as triangles. Vertices are stored in the callee ImDrawList's vtx_buffer[] array, indices in idx_buffer[].
1827 ImVec4 ClipRect; // Clipping rectangle (x1, y1, x2, y2). Subtract ImDrawData->DisplayPos to get clipping rectangle in "viewport" coordinates
1828 ImTextureID TextureId; // User-provided texture ID. Set by user in ImfontAtlas::SetTexID() for fonts or passed to Image*() functions. Ignore if never using images or multiple fonts atlas.
1829 unsigned int VtxOffset; // Start offset in vertex buffer. Pre-1.71 or without ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset: always 0. With ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset: may be >0 to support meshes larger than 64K vertices with 16-bit indices.
1830 unsigned int IdxOffset; // Start offset in index buffer. Always equal to sum of ElemCount drawn so far.
1831 ImDrawCallback UserCallback; // If != NULL, call the function instead of rendering the vertices. clip_rect and texture_id will be set normally.
1832 void* UserCallbackData; // The draw callback code can access this.
1833
1834 ImDrawCmd() { ElemCount = 0; TextureId = (ImTextureID)NULL; VtxOffset = IdxOffset = 0; UserCallback = NULL; UserCallbackData = NULL; }
1835};
1836
1837// Vertex index
1838// (to allow large meshes with 16-bit indices: set 'io.BackendFlags |= ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' and handle ImDrawCmd::VtxOffset in the renderer back-end)
1839// (to use 32-bit indices: override with '#define ImDrawIdx unsigned int' in imconfig.h)
1840#ifndef ImDrawIdx
1841typedef unsigned short ImDrawIdx;
1842#endif
1843
1844// Vertex layout
1845#ifndef IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT
1846struct ImDrawVert
1847{
1848 ImVec2 pos;
1849 ImVec2 uv;
1850 ImU32 col;
1851};
1852#else
1853// You can override the vertex format layout by defining IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT in imconfig.h
1854// The code expect ImVec2 pos (8 bytes), ImVec2 uv (8 bytes), ImU32 col (4 bytes), but you can re-order them or add other fields as needed to simplify integration in your engine.
1855// The type has to be described within the macro (you can either declare the struct or use a typedef). This is because ImVec2/ImU32 are likely not declared a the time you'd want to set your type up.
1856// NOTE: IMGUI DOESN'T CLEAR THE STRUCTURE AND DOESN'T CALL A CONSTRUCTOR SO ANY CUSTOM FIELD WILL BE UNINITIALIZED. IF YOU ADD EXTRA FIELDS (SUCH AS A 'Z' COORDINATES) YOU WILL NEED TO CLEAR THEM DURING RENDER OR TO IGNORE THEM.
1857IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT;
1858#endif
1859
1860// For use by ImDrawListSplitter.
1861struct ImDrawChannel
1862{
1863 ImVector<ImDrawCmd> _CmdBuffer;
1864 ImVector<ImDrawIdx> _IdxBuffer;
1865};
1866
1867// Split/Merge functions are used to split the draw list into different layers which can be drawn into out of order.
1868// This is used by the Columns api, so items of each column can be batched together in a same draw call.
1869struct ImDrawListSplitter
1870{
1871 int _Current; // Current channel number (0)
1872 int _Count; // Number of active channels (1+)
1873 ImVector<ImDrawChannel> _Channels; // Draw channels (not resized down so _Count might be < Channels.Size)
1874
1875 inline ImDrawListSplitter() { Clear(); }
1876 inline ~ImDrawListSplitter() { ClearFreeMemory(); }
1877 inline void Clear() { _Current = 0; _Count = 1; } // Do not clear Channels[] so our allocations are reused next frame
1878 IMGUI_API void ClearFreeMemory();
1879 IMGUI_API void Split(ImDrawList* draw_list, int count);
1880 IMGUI_API void Merge(ImDrawList* draw_list);
1881 IMGUI_API void SetCurrentChannel(ImDrawList* draw_list, int channel_idx);
1882};
1883
1884enum ImDrawCornerFlags_
1885{
1886 ImDrawCornerFlags_None = 0,
1887 ImDrawCornerFlags_TopLeft = 1 << 0, // 0x1
1888 ImDrawCornerFlags_TopRight = 1 << 1, // 0x2
1889 ImDrawCornerFlags_BotLeft = 1 << 2, // 0x4
1890 ImDrawCornerFlags_BotRight = 1 << 3, // 0x8
1891 ImDrawCornerFlags_Top = ImDrawCornerFlags_TopLeft | ImDrawCornerFlags_TopRight, // 0x3
1892 ImDrawCornerFlags_Bot = ImDrawCornerFlags_BotLeft | ImDrawCornerFlags_BotRight, // 0xC
1893 ImDrawCornerFlags_Left = ImDrawCornerFlags_TopLeft | ImDrawCornerFlags_BotLeft, // 0x5
1894 ImDrawCornerFlags_Right = ImDrawCornerFlags_TopRight | ImDrawCornerFlags_BotRight, // 0xA
1895 ImDrawCornerFlags_All = 0xF // In your function calls you may use ~0 (= all bits sets) instead of ImDrawCornerFlags_All, as a convenience
1896};
1897
1898enum ImDrawListFlags_
1899{
1900 ImDrawListFlags_None = 0,
1901 ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedLines = 1 << 0, // Lines are anti-aliased (*2 the number of triangles for 1.0f wide line, otherwise *3 the number of triangles)
1902 ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedFill = 1 << 1, // Filled shapes have anti-aliased edges (*2 the number of vertices)
1903 ImDrawListFlags_AllowVtxOffset = 1 << 2 // Can emit 'VtxOffset > 0' to allow large meshes. Set when 'ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' is enabled.
1904};
1905
1906// Draw command list
1907// This is the low-level list of polygons that ImGui:: functions are filling. At the end of the frame,
1908// all command lists are passed to your ImGuiIO::RenderDrawListFn function for rendering.
1909// Each dear imgui window contains its own ImDrawList. You can use ImGui::GetWindowDrawList() to
1910// access the current window draw list and draw custom primitives.
1911// You can interleave normal ImGui:: calls and adding primitives to the current draw list.
1912// All positions are generally in pixel coordinates (top-left at (0,0), bottom-right at io.DisplaySize), but you are totally free to apply whatever transformation matrix to want to the data (if you apply such transformation you'll want to apply it to ClipRect as well)
1913// Important: Primitives are always added to the list and not culled (culling is done at higher-level by ImGui:: functions), if you use this API a lot consider coarse culling your drawn objects.
1914struct ImDrawList
1915{
1916 // This is what you have to render
1917 ImVector<ImDrawCmd> CmdBuffer; // Draw commands. Typically 1 command = 1 GPU draw call, unless the command is a callback.
1918 ImVector<ImDrawIdx> IdxBuffer; // Index buffer. Each command consume ImDrawCmd::ElemCount of those
1919 ImVector<ImDrawVert> VtxBuffer; // Vertex buffer.
1920 ImDrawListFlags Flags; // Flags, you may poke into these to adjust anti-aliasing settings per-primitive.
1921
1922 // [Internal, used while building lists]
1923 const ImDrawListSharedData* _Data; // Pointer to shared draw data (you can use ImGui::GetDrawListSharedData() to get the one from current ImGui context)
1924 const char* _OwnerName; // Pointer to owner window's name for debugging
1925 unsigned int _VtxCurrentOffset; // [Internal] Always 0 unless 'Flags & ImDrawListFlags_AllowVtxOffset'.
1926 unsigned int _VtxCurrentIdx; // [Internal] Generally == VtxBuffer.Size unless we are past 64K vertices, in which case this gets reset to 0.
1927 ImDrawVert* _VtxWritePtr; // [Internal] point within VtxBuffer.Data after each add command (to avoid using the ImVector<> operators too much)
1928 ImDrawIdx* _IdxWritePtr; // [Internal] point within IdxBuffer.Data after each add command (to avoid using the ImVector<> operators too much)
1929 ImVector<ImVec4> _ClipRectStack; // [Internal]
1930 ImVector<ImTextureID> _TextureIdStack; // [Internal]
1931 ImVector<ImVec2> _Path; // [Internal] current path building
1932 ImDrawListSplitter _Splitter; // [Internal] for channels api
1933
1934 // If you want to create ImDrawList instances, pass them ImGui::GetDrawListSharedData() or create and use your own ImDrawListSharedData (so you can use ImDrawList without ImGui)
1935 ImDrawList(const ImDrawListSharedData* shared_data) { _Data = shared_data; _OwnerName = NULL; Clear(); }
1936 ~ImDrawList() { ClearFreeMemory(); }
1937 IMGUI_API void PushClipRect(ImVec2 clip_rect_min, ImVec2 clip_rect_max, bool intersect_with_current_clip_rect = false); // Render-level scissoring. This is passed down to your render function but not used for CPU-side coarse clipping. Prefer using higher-level ImGui::PushClipRect() to affect logic (hit-testing and widget culling)
1938 IMGUI_API void PushClipRectFullScreen();
1939 IMGUI_API void PopClipRect();
1940 IMGUI_API void PushTextureID(ImTextureID texture_id);
1941 IMGUI_API void PopTextureID();
1942 inline ImVec2 GetClipRectMin() const { const ImVec4& cr = _ClipRectStack.back(); return ImVec2(cr.x, cr.y); }
1943 inline ImVec2 GetClipRectMax() const { const ImVec4& cr = _ClipRectStack.back(); return ImVec2(cr.z, cr.w); }
1944
1945 // Primitives
1946 // - For rectangular primitives, "p_min" and "p_max" represent the upper-left and lower-right corners.
1947 // - For circle primitives, use "num_segments == 0" to automatically calculate tessellation (preferred).
1948 // In future versions we will use textures to provide cheaper and higher-quality circles.
1949 // Use AddNgon() and AddNgonFilled() functions if you need to guaranteed a specific number of sides.
1950 IMGUI_API void AddLine(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, ImU32 col, float thickness = 1.0f);
1951 IMGUI_API void AddRect(const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, ImU32 col, float rounding = 0.0f, ImDrawCornerFlags rounding_corners = ImDrawCornerFlags_All, float thickness = 1.0f); // a: upper-left, b: lower-right (== upper-left + size), rounding_corners_flags: 4 bits corresponding to which corner to round
1952 IMGUI_API void AddRectFilled(const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, ImU32 col, float rounding = 0.0f, ImDrawCornerFlags rounding_corners = ImDrawCornerFlags_All); // a: upper-left, b: lower-right (== upper-left + size)
1953 IMGUI_API void AddRectFilledMultiColor(const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, ImU32 col_upr_left, ImU32 col_upr_right, ImU32 col_bot_right, ImU32 col_bot_left);
1954 IMGUI_API void AddQuad(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col, float thickness = 1.0f);
1955 IMGUI_API void AddQuadFilled(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col);
1956 IMGUI_API void AddTriangle(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, ImU32 col, float thickness = 1.0f);
1957 IMGUI_API void AddTriangleFilled(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, ImU32 col);
1958 IMGUI_API void AddCircle(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments = 12, float thickness = 1.0f);
1959 IMGUI_API void AddCircleFilled(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments = 12);
1960 IMGUI_API void AddNgon(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments, float thickness = 1.0f);
1961 IMGUI_API void AddNgonFilled(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments);
1962 IMGUI_API void AddText(const ImVec2& pos, ImU32 col, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end = NULL);
1963 IMGUI_API void AddText(const ImFont* font, float font_size, const ImVec2& pos, ImU32 col, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end = NULL, float wrap_width = 0.0f, const ImVec4* cpu_fine_clip_rect = NULL);
1964 IMGUI_API void AddPolyline(const ImVec2* points, int num_points, ImU32 col, bool closed, float thickness);
1965 IMGUI_API void AddConvexPolyFilled(const ImVec2* points, int num_points, ImU32 col); // Note: Anti-aliased filling requires points to be in clockwise order.
1966 IMGUI_API void AddBezierCurve(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col, float thickness, int num_segments = 0);
1967
1968 // Image primitives
1969 // - Read FAQ to understand what ImTextureID is.
1970 // - "p_min" and "p_max" represent the upper-left and lower-right corners of the rectangle.
1971 // - "uv_min" and "uv_max" represent the normalized texture coordinates to use for those corners. Using (0,0)->(1,1) texture coordinates will generally display the entire texture.
1972 IMGUI_API void AddImage(ImTextureID user_texture_id, const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, const ImVec2& uv_min = ImVec2(0, 0), const ImVec2& uv_max = ImVec2(1, 1), ImU32 col = IM_COL32_WHITE);
1973 IMGUI_API void AddImageQuad(ImTextureID user_texture_id, const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, const ImVec2& uv1 = ImVec2(0, 0), const ImVec2& uv2 = ImVec2(1, 0), const ImVec2& uv3 = ImVec2(1, 1), const ImVec2& uv4 = ImVec2(0, 1), ImU32 col = IM_COL32_WHITE);
1974 IMGUI_API void AddImageRounded(ImTextureID user_texture_id, const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, const ImVec2& uv_min, const ImVec2& uv_max, ImU32 col, float rounding, ImDrawCornerFlags rounding_corners = ImDrawCornerFlags_All);
1975
1976 // Stateful path API, add points then finish with PathFillConvex() or PathStroke()
1977 inline void PathClear() { _Path.Size = 0; }
1978 inline void PathLineTo(const ImVec2& pos) { _Path.push_back(pos); }
1979 inline void PathLineToMergeDuplicate(const ImVec2& pos) { if (_Path.Size == 0 || memcmp(&_Path.Data[_Path.Size-1], &pos, 8) != 0) _Path.push_back(pos); }
1980 inline void PathFillConvex(ImU32 col) { AddConvexPolyFilled(_Path.Data, _Path.Size, col); _Path.Size = 0; } // Note: Anti-aliased filling requires points to be in clockwise order.
1981 inline void PathStroke(ImU32 col, bool closed, float thickness = 1.0f) { AddPolyline(_Path.Data, _Path.Size, col, closed, thickness); _Path.Size = 0; }
1982 IMGUI_API void PathArcTo(const ImVec2& center, float radius, float a_min, float a_max, int num_segments = 10);
1983 IMGUI_API void PathArcToFast(const ImVec2& center, float radius, int a_min_of_12, int a_max_of_12); // Use precomputed angles for a 12 steps circle
1984 IMGUI_API void PathBezierCurveTo(const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, int num_segments = 0);
1985 IMGUI_API void PathRect(const ImVec2& rect_min, const ImVec2& rect_max, float rounding = 0.0f, ImDrawCornerFlags rounding_corners = ImDrawCornerFlags_All);
1986
1987 // Advanced
1988 IMGUI_API void AddCallback(ImDrawCallback callback, void* callback_data); // Your rendering function must check for 'UserCallback' in ImDrawCmd and call the function instead of rendering triangles.
1989 IMGUI_API void AddDrawCmd(); // This is useful if you need to forcefully create a new draw call (to allow for dependent rendering / blending). Otherwise primitives are merged into the same draw-call as much as possible
1990 IMGUI_API ImDrawList* CloneOutput() const; // Create a clone of the CmdBuffer/IdxBuffer/VtxBuffer.
1991
1992 // Advanced: Channels
1993 // - Use to split render into layers. By switching channels to can render out-of-order (e.g. submit FG primitives before BG primitives)
1994 // - Use to minimize draw calls (e.g. if going back-and-forth between multiple clipping rectangles, prefer to append into separate channels then merge at the end)
1995 // - FIXME-OBSOLETE: This API shouldn't have been in ImDrawList in the first place!
1996 // Prefer using your own persistent copy of ImDrawListSplitter as you can stack them.
1997 // Using the ImDrawList::ChannelsXXXX you cannot stack a split over another.
1998 inline void ChannelsSplit(int count) { _Splitter.Split(this, count); }
1999 inline void ChannelsMerge() { _Splitter.Merge(this); }
2000 inline void ChannelsSetCurrent(int n) { _Splitter.SetCurrentChannel(this, n); }
2001
2002 // Internal helpers
2003 // NB: all primitives needs to be reserved via PrimReserve() beforehand!
2004 IMGUI_API void Clear();
2005 IMGUI_API void ClearFreeMemory();
2006 IMGUI_API void PrimReserve(int idx_count, int vtx_count);
2007 IMGUI_API void PrimUnreserve(int idx_count, int vtx_count);
2008 IMGUI_API void PrimRect(const ImVec2& a, const ImVec2& b, ImU32 col); // Axis aligned rectangle (composed of two triangles)
2009 IMGUI_API void PrimRectUV(const ImVec2& a, const ImVec2& b, const ImVec2& uv_a, const ImVec2& uv_b, ImU32 col);
2010 IMGUI_API void PrimQuadUV(const ImVec2& a, const ImVec2& b, const ImVec2& c, const ImVec2& d, const ImVec2& uv_a, const ImVec2& uv_b, const ImVec2& uv_c, const ImVec2& uv_d, ImU32 col);
2011 inline void PrimWriteVtx(const ImVec2& pos, const ImVec2& uv, ImU32 col){ _VtxWritePtr->pos = pos; _VtxWritePtr->uv = uv; _VtxWritePtr->col = col; _VtxWritePtr++; _VtxCurrentIdx++; }
2012 inline void PrimWriteIdx(ImDrawIdx idx) { *_IdxWritePtr = idx; _IdxWritePtr++; }
2013 inline void PrimVtx(const ImVec2& pos, const ImVec2& uv, ImU32 col) { PrimWriteIdx((ImDrawIdx)_VtxCurrentIdx); PrimWriteVtx(pos, uv, col); }
2014 IMGUI_API void UpdateClipRect();
2015 IMGUI_API void UpdateTextureID();
2016};

2018// All draw data to render a Dear ImGui frame
2019// (NB: the style and the naming convention here is a little inconsistent, we currently preserve them for backward compatibility purpose,
2020// as this is one of the oldest structure exposed by the library! Basically, ImDrawList == CmdList)
2021struct ImDrawData
2022{
2023 bool Valid; // Only valid after Render() is called and before the next NewFrame() is called.
2024 ImDrawList** CmdLists; // Array of ImDrawList* to render. The ImDrawList are owned by ImGuiContext and only pointed to from here.
2025 int CmdListsCount; // Number of ImDrawList* to render
2026 int TotalIdxCount; // For convenience, sum of all ImDrawList's IdxBuffer.Size
2027 int TotalVtxCount; // For convenience, sum of all ImDrawList's VtxBuffer.Size
2028 ImVec2 DisplayPos; // Upper-left position of the viewport to render (== upper-left of the orthogonal projection matrix to use)
2029 ImVec2 DisplaySize; // Size of the viewport to render (== io.DisplaySize for the main viewport) (DisplayPos + DisplaySize == lower-right of the orthogonal projection matrix to use)
2030 ImVec2 FramebufferScale; // Amount of pixels for each unit of DisplaySize. Based on io.DisplayFramebufferScale. Generally (1,1) on normal display, (2,2) on OSX with Retina display.
2031
2032 // Functions
2033 ImDrawData() { Valid = false; Clear(); }
2034 ~ImDrawData() { Clear(); }
2035 void Clear() { Valid = false; CmdLists = NULL; CmdListsCount = TotalVtxCount = TotalIdxCount = 0; DisplayPos = DisplaySize = FramebufferScale = ImVec2(0.f, 0.f); } // The ImDrawList are owned by ImGuiContext!
2036 IMGUI_API void DeIndexAllBuffers(); // Helper to convert all buffers from indexed to non-indexed, in case you cannot render indexed. Note: this is slow and most likely a waste of resources. Always prefer indexed rendering!
2037 IMGUI_API void ScaleClipRects(const ImVec2& fb_scale); // Helper to scale the ClipRect field of each ImDrawCmd. Use if your final output buffer is at a different scale than Dear ImGui expects, or if there is a difference between your window resolution and framebuffer resolution.
2038};

2040//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2041// Font API (ImFontConfig, ImFontGlyph, ImFontAtlasFlags, ImFontAtlas, ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder, ImFont)
2042//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2043
2044struct ImFontConfig
2045{
2046 void* FontData; // // TTF/OTF data
2047 int FontDataSize; // // TTF/OTF data size
2048 bool FontDataOwnedByAtlas; // true // TTF/OTF data ownership taken by the container ImFontAtlas (will delete memory itself).
2049 int FontNo; // 0 // Index of font within TTF/OTF file
2050 float SizePixels; // // Size in pixels for rasterizer (more or less maps to the resulting font height).
2051 int OversampleH; // 3 // Rasterize at higher quality for sub-pixel positioning. Read https://github.com/nothings/stb/blob/master/tests/oversample/README.md for details.
2052 int OversampleV; // 1 // Rasterize at higher quality for sub-pixel positioning. We don't use sub-pixel positions on the Y axis.
2053 bool PixelSnapH; // false // Align every glyph to pixel boundary. Useful e.g. if you are merging a non-pixel aligned font with the default font. If enabled, you can set OversampleH/V to 1.
2054 ImVec2 GlyphExtraSpacing; // 0, 0 // Extra spacing (in pixels) between glyphs. Only X axis is supported for now.
2055 ImVec2 GlyphOffset; // 0, 0 // Offset all glyphs from this font input.
2056 const ImWchar* GlyphRanges; // NULL // Pointer to a user-provided list of Unicode range (2 value per range, values are inclusive, zero-terminated list). THE ARRAY DATA NEEDS TO PERSIST AS LONG AS THE FONT IS ALIVE.
2057 float GlyphMinAdvanceX; // 0 // Minimum AdvanceX for glyphs, set Min to align font icons, set both Min/Max to enforce mono-space font
2058 float GlyphMaxAdvanceX; // FLT_MAX // Maximum AdvanceX for glyphs
2059 bool MergeMode; // false // Merge into previous ImFont, so you can combine multiple inputs font into one ImFont (e.g. ASCII font + icons + Japanese glyphs). You may want to use GlyphOffset.y when merge font of different heights.
2060 unsigned int RasterizerFlags; // 0x00 // Settings for custom font rasterizer (e.g. ImGuiFreeType). Leave as zero if you aren't using one.
2061 float RasterizerMultiply; // 1.0f // Brighten (>1.0f) or darken (<1.0f) font output. Brightening small fonts may be a good workaround to make them more readable.
2062 ImWchar EllipsisChar; // -1 // Explicitly specify unicode codepoint of ellipsis character. When fonts are being merged first specified ellipsis will be used.
2063
2064 // [Internal]
2065 char Name[40]; // Name (strictly to ease debugging)
2066 ImFont* DstFont;
2067
2068 IMGUI_API ImFontConfig();
2069};
2070
2071struct ImFontGlyph
2072{
2073 ImWchar Codepoint; // 0x0000..0xFFFF
2074 float AdvanceX; // Distance to next character (= data from font + ImFontConfig::GlyphExtraSpacing.x baked in)
2075 float X0, Y0, X1, Y1; // Glyph corners
2076 float U0, V0, U1, V1; // Texture coordinates
2077};
2078
2079// Helper to build glyph ranges from text/string data. Feed your application strings/characters to it then call BuildRanges().
2080// This is essentially a tightly packed of vector of 64k booleans = 8KB storage.
2081struct ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder
2082{
2083 ImVector<ImU32> UsedChars; // Store 1-bit per Unicode code point (0=unused, 1=used)
2084
2085 ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder() { Clear(); }
2086 inline void Clear() { int size_in_bytes = (IM_UNICODE_CODEPOINT_MAX+1) / 8; UsedChars.resize(size_in_bytes / (int)sizeof(ImU32)); memset(UsedChars.Data, 0, (size_t)size_in_bytes); }
2087 inline bool GetBit(int n) const { int off = (n >> 5); ImU32 mask = 1u << (n & 31); return (UsedChars[off] & mask) != 0; } // Get bit n in the array
2088 inline void SetBit(int n) { int off = (n >> 5); ImU32 mask = 1u << (n & 31); UsedChars[off] |= mask; } // Set bit n in the array
2089 inline void AddChar(ImWchar c) { SetBit(c); } // Add character
2090 IMGUI_API void AddText(const char* text, const char* text_end = NULL); // Add string (each character of the UTF-8 string are added)
2091 IMGUI_API void AddRanges(const ImWchar* ranges); // Add ranges, e.g. builder.AddRanges(ImFontAtlas::GetGlyphRangesDefault()) to force add all of ASCII/Latin+Ext
2092 IMGUI_API void BuildRanges(ImVector<ImWchar>* out_ranges); // Output new ranges
2093};
2094
2095// See ImFontAtlas::AddCustomRectXXX functions.
2096struct ImFontAtlasCustomRect
2097{
2098 unsigned int ID; // Input // User ID. Use < 0x110000 to map into a font glyph, >= 0x110000 for other/internal/custom texture data.
2099 unsigned short Width, Height; // Input // Desired rectangle dimension
2100 unsigned short X, Y; // Output // Packed position in Atlas
2101 float GlyphAdvanceX; // Input // For custom font glyphs only (ID < 0x110000): glyph xadvance
2102 ImVec2 GlyphOffset; // Input // For custom font glyphs only (ID < 0x110000): glyph display offset
2103 ImFont* Font; // Input // For custom font glyphs only (ID < 0x110000): target font
2104 ImFontAtlasCustomRect() { ID = 0xFFFFFFFF; Width = Height = 0; X = Y = 0xFFFF; GlyphAdvanceX = 0.0f; GlyphOffset = ImVec2(0,0); Font = NULL; }
2105 bool IsPacked() const { return X != 0xFFFF; }
2106};
2107
2108enum ImFontAtlasFlags_
2109{
2110 ImFontAtlasFlags_None = 0,
2111 ImFontAtlasFlags_NoPowerOfTwoHeight = 1 << 0, // Don't round the height to next power of two
2112 ImFontAtlasFlags_NoMouseCursors = 1 << 1 // Don't build software mouse cursors into the atlas
2113};
2114
2115// Load and rasterize multiple TTF/OTF fonts into a same texture. The font atlas will build a single texture holding:
2116// - One or more fonts.
2117// - Custom graphics data needed to render the shapes needed by Dear ImGui.
2118// - Mouse cursor shapes for software cursor rendering (unless setting 'Flags |= ImFontAtlasFlags_NoMouseCursors' in the font atlas).
2119// It is the user-code responsibility to setup/build the atlas, then upload the pixel data into a texture accessible by your graphics api.
2120// - Optionally, call any of the AddFont*** functions. If you don't call any, the default font embedded in the code will be loaded for you.
2121// - Call GetTexDataAsAlpha8() or GetTexDataAsRGBA32() to build and retrieve pixels data.
2122// - Upload the pixels data into a texture within your graphics system (see imgui_impl_xxxx.cpp examples)
2123// - Call SetTexID(my_tex_id); and pass the pointer/identifier to your texture in a format natural to your graphics API.
2124// This value will be passed back to you during rendering to identify the texture. Read FAQ entry about ImTextureID for more details.
2125// Common pitfalls:
2126// - If you pass a 'glyph_ranges' array to AddFont*** functions, you need to make sure that your array persist up until the
2127// atlas is build (when calling GetTexData*** or Build()). We only copy the pointer, not the data.
2128// - Important: By default, AddFontFromMemoryTTF() takes ownership of the data. Even though we are not writing to it, we will free the pointer on destruction.
2129// You can set font_cfg->FontDataOwnedByAtlas=false to keep ownership of your data and it won't be freed,
2130// - Even though many functions are suffixed with "TTF", OTF data is supported just as well.
2131// - This is an old API and it is currently awkward for those and and various other reasons! We will address them in the future!
2132struct ImFontAtlas
2133{
2134 IMGUI_API ImFontAtlas();
2135 IMGUI_API ~ImFontAtlas();
2136 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFont(const ImFontConfig* font_cfg);
2137 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontDefault(const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL);
2138 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromFileTTF(const char* filename, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL);
2139 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromMemoryTTF(void* font_data, int font_size, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL); // Note: Transfer ownership of 'ttf_data' to ImFontAtlas! Will be deleted after destruction of the atlas. Set font_cfg->FontDataOwnedByAtlas=false to keep ownership of your data and it won't be freed.
2140 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromMemoryCompressedTTF(const void* compressed_font_data, int compressed_font_size, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL); // 'compressed_font_data' still owned by caller. Compress with binary_to_compressed_c.cpp.
2141 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromMemoryCompressedBase85TTF(const char* compressed_font_data_base85, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL); // 'compressed_font_data_base85' still owned by caller. Compress with binary_to_compressed_c.cpp with -base85 parameter.
2142 IMGUI_API void ClearInputData(); // Clear input data (all ImFontConfig structures including sizes, TTF data, glyph ranges, etc.) = all the data used to build the texture and fonts.
2143 IMGUI_API void ClearTexData(); // Clear output texture data (CPU side). Saves RAM once the texture has been copied to graphics memory.
2144 IMGUI_API void ClearFonts(); // Clear output font data (glyphs storage, UV coordinates).
2145 IMGUI_API void Clear(); // Clear all input and output.
2146
2147 // Build atlas, retrieve pixel data.
2148 // User is in charge of copying the pixels into graphics memory (e.g. create a texture with your engine). Then store your texture handle with SetTexID().
2149 // The pitch is always = Width * BytesPerPixels (1 or 4)
2150 // Building in RGBA32 format is provided for convenience and compatibility, but note that unless you manually manipulate or copy color data into
2151 // the texture (e.g. when using the AddCustomRect*** api), then the RGB pixels emitted will always be white (~75% of memory/bandwidth waste.
2152 IMGUI_API bool Build(); // Build pixels data. This is called automatically for you by the GetTexData*** functions.
2153 IMGUI_API void GetTexDataAsAlpha8(unsigned char** out_pixels, int* out_width, int* out_height, int* out_bytes_per_pixel = NULL); // 1 byte per-pixel
2154 IMGUI_API void GetTexDataAsRGBA32(unsigned char** out_pixels, int* out_width, int* out_height, int* out_bytes_per_pixel = NULL); // 4 bytes-per-pixel
2155 bool IsBuilt() const { return Fonts.Size > 0 && (TexPixelsAlpha8 != NULL || TexPixelsRGBA32 != NULL); }
2156 void SetTexID(ImTextureID id) { TexID = id; }
2157
2158 //-------------------------------------------
2159 // Glyph Ranges
2160 //-------------------------------------------
2161
2162 // Helpers to retrieve list of common Unicode ranges (2 value per range, values are inclusive, zero-terminated list)
2163 // NB: Make sure that your string are UTF-8 and NOT in your local code page. In C++11, you can create UTF-8 string literal using the u8"Hello world" syntax. See FAQ for details.
2164 // NB: Consider using ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder to build glyph ranges from textual data.
2165 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesDefault(); // Basic Latin, Extended Latin
2166 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesKorean(); // Default + Korean characters
2167 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesJapanese(); // Default + Hiragana, Katakana, Half-Width, Selection of 1946 Ideographs
2168 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesChineseFull(); // Default + Half-Width + Japanese Hiragana/Katakana + full set of about 21000 CJK Unified Ideographs
2169 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesChineseSimplifiedCommon();// Default + Half-Width + Japanese Hiragana/Katakana + set of 2500 CJK Unified Ideographs for common simplified Chinese
2170 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesCyrillic(); // Default + about 400 Cyrillic characters
2171 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesThai(); // Default + Thai characters
2172 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesVietnamese(); // Default + Vietnamese characters

2174 //-------------------------------------------
2175 // [BETA] Custom Rectangles/Glyphs API
2176 //-------------------------------------------
2177
2178 // You can request arbitrary rectangles to be packed into the atlas, for your own purposes.
2179 // After calling Build(), you can query the rectangle position and render your pixels.
2180 // You can also request your rectangles to be mapped as font glyph (given a font + Unicode point),
2181 // so you can render e.g. custom colorful icons and use them as regular glyphs.
2182 // Read docs/FONTS.txt for more details about using colorful icons.
2183 IMGUI_API int AddCustomRectRegular(unsigned int id, int width, int height); // Id needs to be >= 0x110000. Id >= 0x80000000 are reserved for ImGui and ImDrawList
2184 IMGUI_API int AddCustomRectFontGlyph(ImFont* font, ImWchar id, int width, int height, float advance_x, const ImVec2& offset = ImVec2(0,0)); // Id needs to be < 0x110000 to register a rectangle to map into a specific font.
2185 const ImFontAtlasCustomRect*GetCustomRectByIndex(int index) const { if (index < 0) return NULL; return &CustomRects[index]; }
2186
2187 // [Internal]
2188 IMGUI_API void CalcCustomRectUV(const ImFontAtlasCustomRect* rect, ImVec2* out_uv_min, ImVec2* out_uv_max) const;
2189 IMGUI_API bool GetMouseCursorTexData(ImGuiMouseCursor cursor, ImVec2* out_offset, ImVec2* out_size, ImVec2 out_uv_border[2], ImVec2 out_uv_fill[2]);
2190
2191 //-------------------------------------------
2192 // Members
2193 //-------------------------------------------
2194
2195 bool Locked; // Marked as Locked by ImGui::NewFrame() so attempt to modify the atlas will assert.
2196 ImFontAtlasFlags Flags; // Build flags (see ImFontAtlasFlags_)
2197 ImTextureID TexID; // User data to refer to the texture once it has been uploaded to user's graphic systems. It is passed back to you during rendering via the ImDrawCmd structure.
2198 int TexDesiredWidth; // Texture width desired by user before Build(). Must be a power-of-two. If have many glyphs your graphics API have texture size restrictions you may want to increase texture width to decrease height.
2199 int TexGlyphPadding; // Padding between glyphs within texture in pixels. Defaults to 1. If your rendering method doesn't rely on bilinear filtering you may set this to 0.
2200
2201 // [Internal]
2202 // NB: Access texture data via GetTexData*() calls! Which will setup a default font for you.
2203 unsigned char* TexPixelsAlpha8; // 1 component per pixel, each component is unsigned 8-bit. Total size = TexWidth * TexHeight
2204 unsigned int* TexPixelsRGBA32; // 4 component per pixel, each component is unsigned 8-bit. Total size = TexWidth * TexHeight * 4
2205 int TexWidth; // Texture width calculated during Build().
2206 int TexHeight; // Texture height calculated during Build().
2207 ImVec2 TexUvScale; // = (1.0f/TexWidth, 1.0f/TexHeight)
2208 ImVec2 TexUvWhitePixel; // Texture coordinates to a white pixel
2209 ImVector<ImFont*> Fonts; // Hold all the fonts returned by AddFont*. Fonts[0] is the default font upon calling ImGui::NewFrame(), use ImGui::PushFont()/PopFont() to change the current font.
2210 ImVector<ImFontAtlasCustomRect> CustomRects; // Rectangles for packing custom texture data into the atlas.
2211 ImVector<ImFontConfig> ConfigData; // Internal data
2212 int CustomRectIds[1]; // Identifiers of custom texture rectangle used by ImFontAtlas/ImDrawList
2213
2214#ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
2215 typedef ImFontAtlasCustomRect CustomRect; // OBSOLETED in 1.72+
2216 typedef ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder GlyphRangesBuilder; // OBSOLETED in 1.67+
2217#endif
2218};

2220// Font runtime data and rendering
2221// ImFontAtlas automatically loads a default embedded font for you when you call GetTexDataAsAlpha8() or GetTexDataAsRGBA32().
2222struct ImFont
2223{
2224 // Members: Hot ~20/24 bytes (for CalcTextSize)
2225 ImVector<float> IndexAdvanceX; // 12-16 // out // // Sparse. Glyphs->AdvanceX in a directly indexable way (cache-friendly for CalcTextSize functions which only this this info, and are often bottleneck in large UI).
2226 float FallbackAdvanceX; // 4 // out // = FallbackGlyph->AdvanceX
2227 float FontSize; // 4 // in // // Height of characters/line, set during loading (don't change after loading)
2228
2229 // Members: Hot ~36/48 bytes (for CalcTextSize + render loop)
2230 ImVector<ImWchar> IndexLookup; // 12-16 // out // // Sparse. Index glyphs by Unicode code-point.
2231 ImVector<ImFontGlyph> Glyphs; // 12-16 // out // // All glyphs.
2232 const ImFontGlyph* FallbackGlyph; // 4-8 // out // = FindGlyph(FontFallbackChar)
2233 ImVec2 DisplayOffset; // 8 // in // = (0,0) // Offset font rendering by xx pixels
2234
2235 // Members: Cold ~32/40 bytes
2236 ImFontAtlas* ContainerAtlas; // 4-8 // out // // What we has been loaded into
2237 const ImFontConfig* ConfigData; // 4-8 // in // // Pointer within ContainerAtlas->ConfigData
2238 short ConfigDataCount; // 2 // in // ~ 1 // Number of ImFontConfig involved in creating this font. Bigger than 1 when merging multiple font sources into one ImFont.
2239 ImWchar FallbackChar; // 2 // in // = '?' // Replacement character if a glyph isn't found. Only set via SetFallbackChar()
2240 ImWchar EllipsisChar; // 2 // out // = -1 // Character used for ellipsis rendering.
2241 bool DirtyLookupTables; // 1 // out //
2242 float Scale; // 4 // in // = 1.f // Base font scale, multiplied by the per-window font scale which you can adjust with SetWindowFontScale()
2243 float Ascent, Descent; // 4+4 // out // // Ascent: distance from top to bottom of e.g. 'A' [0..FontSize]
2244 int MetricsTotalSurface;// 4 // out // // Total surface in pixels to get an idea of the font rasterization/texture cost (not exact, we approximate the cost of padding between glyphs)
2245
2246 // Methods
2247 IMGUI_API ImFont();
2248 IMGUI_API ~ImFont();
2249 IMGUI_API const ImFontGlyph*FindGlyph(ImWchar c) const;
2250 IMGUI_API const ImFontGlyph*FindGlyphNoFallback(ImWchar c) const;
2251 float GetCharAdvance(ImWchar c) const { return ((int)c < IndexAdvanceX.Size) ? IndexAdvanceX[(int)c] : FallbackAdvanceX; }
2252 bool IsLoaded() const { return ContainerAtlas != NULL; }
2253 const char* GetDebugName() const { return ConfigData ? ConfigData->Name : "<unknown>"; }
2254
2255 // 'max_width' stops rendering after a certain width (could be turned into a 2d size). FLT_MAX to disable.
2256 // 'wrap_width' enable automatic word-wrapping across multiple lines to fit into given width. 0.0f to disable.
2257 IMGUI_API ImVec2 CalcTextSizeA(float size, float max_width, float wrap_width, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end = NULL, const char** remaining = NULL) const; // utf8
2258 IMGUI_API const char* CalcWordWrapPositionA(float scale, const char* text, const char* text_end, float wrap_width) const;
2259 IMGUI_API void RenderChar(ImDrawList* draw_list, float size, ImVec2 pos, ImU32 col, ImWchar c) const;
2260 IMGUI_API void RenderText(ImDrawList* draw_list, float size, ImVec2 pos, ImU32 col, const ImVec4& clip_rect, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end, float wrap_width = 0.0f, bool cpu_fine_clip = false) const;
2261
2262 // [Internal] Don't use!
2263 IMGUI_API void BuildLookupTable();
2264 IMGUI_API void ClearOutputData();
2265 IMGUI_API void GrowIndex(int new_size);
2266 IMGUI_API void AddGlyph(ImWchar c, float x0, float y0, float x1, float y1, float u0, float v0, float u1, float v1, float advance_x);
2267 IMGUI_API void AddRemapChar(ImWchar dst, ImWchar src, bool overwrite_dst = true); // Makes 'dst' character/glyph points to 'src' character/glyph. Currently needs to be called AFTER fonts have been built.
2268 IMGUI_API void SetFallbackChar(ImWchar c);
2269};
